haracters In March Madness Faceoff|author= David Stonecipher |website=[[Inquisitr]]|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Polygon\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/7/30/17630476/dragon-age-hard-in-hightown-book-dark-horse-varric-tethras|date=July 30, 2018 |title= Dragon Age\u2019s fake novel is a real book now, so we interviewed its author, Varric Tethras|author=Susana Polo |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gameinformer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2013/08/15/the-best-bioware-characters.aspx?PostPageIndex=1 |title=The Best BioWare Characters |author=Kimberley Wallace |date=August 15, 2013 |work=Game Informer |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> \n\n<ref name=\"Rock, Paper, Shotgun\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/01/06/dragon-age-varric-publishing-real-novel/|date=January 6, 2018|title=Fictional Dragon Age dwarf publishes actual real novel|author= \nDominic Tarason|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RPGDream\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-rpg-dream-team|date=June 9, 2017 |title=The RPG dream teams|website=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Varric and Morrigan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vg247.com/2014/03/28/dragon-ages-varric-and-morrigan-discuss-voice-acting/ |title=Dragon Age's Varric and Morrigan discuss voice acting |author=Brenna Hillier |date=March 28, 2014 |publisher=VG247 |accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Darrah interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2014/04/22/dragon-age-inquisition-interview-on-fan-feedback-romance-returning-characters-and-the-open-world/ |title=Dragon Age: Inquisition interview - on fan feedback, romance, returning characters and the open world |author=Chris Thursten |date=April 22, 2014 |publisher=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Return\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2014/05/06/the-return-of-varric-in-dragon-age-inquisition.aspx|date=May 6, 2014|title = The Return Of Varric In Dragon Age: Inquisition|author= Kimberley Wallace |website=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kirby interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.heypoorplayer.com/2018/01/10/interview-mary-kirby-hard-in-hightown/|date=January 10, 2018|title = INTERVIEW: BIOWARE\u2019S MARY KIRBY ABOUT UPCOMING DRAGON AGE NOVELLA \u2018HARD IN HIGHTOWN\u2019|author= Aimee Hart|website=Hey Poor Player|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ea.com/en-au/games/dragon-age/dragon-age-inquisition/characters/varric-tethras Varric Tethras] on the official ''Dragon Age: Inquisition'' website\n*[http://blog.bioware.com/2014/02/20/dragon-age-inquisition-character-kits-2/ Character Kits of Cassandra and Varric] on the official BioWare blog\n\n{{Dragon Age}}\n\n[[Category:Dragon Age characters]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video game characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional dwarves]]\n[[Category:Fictional tricksters]]\n[[Category:Dwarves in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2011]]\n[[Category:Video game sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Video game nobility]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox character\n| name            = Varric Tethras\n| series          = [[Dragon Age]]\n| image           = Varric_DAI.png\n| caption         = Varric, as he appears in ''Dragon Age: Inquisition''.\n| first = ''[[Dragon Age II]]'' (2011)\n| voice      = [[Brian Bloom]]\n | lbl21 = Class\n|data21  = Rogue\n| lbl22 = Specialization\n|data22  = Marksman (''Dragon Age II'')<br>Artificer (''Inquisition'')\n| race = Dwarf\n| home = Kirkwall\n}}\n\n'''Varric Tethras''' is a fictional character from [[BioWare|BioWare's]] ''[[Dragon Age]]'' franchise. The character made his debut in 2011's ''[[Dragon Age II]]'', where he appeared as part of the game's [[framing device]] as the [[unreliable narrator]] of its plot. He also serves as a [[Party (role playing games)|party]] member, a role which he reprises in its sequel, ''[[Dragon Age: Inquisition]]''. In-universe, he is a renowned novelist as well as a self-appointed [[celebrity biographer|biographer]] to Hawke and the Inquisitor, the protagonists of ''Dragon Age II'' and ''Dragon Age: Inquisition'' respectively. [[Brian Bloom]] provides the voice for Varric in all media.\n\nVarric has consistently received a positive reception since his debut, with attention drawn to his sense of [[humour]], loyalty, and wisecracking personality. The character's popularity have led BioWare to turn his most notable in-universe work, ''Hard in Hightown'', into a real-world publication. Varric is listed as the first author; the actual novel is written by Mary Kirby, a BioWare employee who is one of the main writers of the ''Dragon Age'' franchise.\n\n==Character overview==\n{{Quote box |width = 25em |align = right |quote = \"But additionally, some characters, Varric's a very good character because one of 'Varric's primary motivations is he's the guy that\u2019s got your back. He's your friend. He\u2019s a very good character to have because it's good to have someone in your camp no matter what. That makes him a very attractive character. It makes him an interesting character to have because he offers a nice counterpoint to a lot of other kinds of characters. |source = \u2014Mike Darrah on Varric's personality.<ref name=\"Darrah interview\"/>}}\n\nVarric is a [[Dwarf (mythology)|dwarf]] from House Tethras, a dwarven noble house which was exiled in disgrace to the surface world from their subterranean homeland, the kingdom of Orzammar, generations prior to the events of ''Dragon Age II''. He is depicted as wielding considerable [[de facto]] political power by virtue of economic assets derived from his family's involvement in trade and commerce. He is considered a merchant prince among the surface dwarves of Thedas, the setting in which the ''Dragon Age'' franchise take place, and has a reputation for being the best dressed man in Kirkwall's Lowtown.<ref name=\"Kits\"/>\n \nVarric claims he runs a \"[[espionage|spy network]]\" with contacts to deal with various troubles that come along with being in a family that is part of the Dwarven Merchants Guild, although he has little interest in their agenda and schemes; he maintains an outward facade as the idle younger scion of his family; while his older brother is in charge of the family business, he usually spends his time in taverns spinning wild stories to the local gamblers and thieves while people buy him drinks. On occasion, his storytelling act is also a cover of him to rob his audience blind.<ref name=\"Kits\"/> Varric is also an accomplished author renowned throughout Thedas; his most notable work is ''Hard in Hightown'', which features the clash between a secretive group of agents of the Chantry's leader Divine with a mysterious organization known as the Executors over a mysterious artifact, with a member of the Kirkwall City Guard, Donnen Brennokovic, caught between the fronts.<ref name=\"Hightown\"/>  \n\nVarric is the only companion member to be a permanent fixture in both ''Dragon Age II'' and ''Dragon Age: Inquisition''; the player will never encounter crisis points with Varric or risk him leaving the party due to his central role in the games' storylines. His loyalty to the player characters of both games is noted by Mike Darrah as a defining character trait.<ref name=\"Darrah interview\"/> His signature weapon is a [[repeating crossbow]] he named Bianca. Bianca has a carved wood stock and brass embellishments, as well as a retractable [[bayonet]] that slides out of a slot in the front. As such, Varric is the only companion who cannot equip alternative ranged weapons in the ''Dragon Age'' series besides his crossbow, which could be upgraded throughout the course of the games. Whenever he is asked about the story behind how Bianca got her name, he replies that it involves a girl and a promise, and that it is the one story that he can never tell.\n\nIn ''Dragon Age II'', Varric is depicted as constantly spinning exaggerated stories about Hawke's heroic deeds. Solving problems and gaining an advantage through diplomacy, lying, and blackmail impresses him, whereas he finds straightforward violence and outright thuggery to be distasteful. He also responds well to irreverent humor and sarcasm. The events of ''Dragon Age II'' evoke his compassion and selflessness, revealing Varric to be a goodhearted person who appreciates kind and thoughtful acts, and who is determined to rebuild Kirkwall after being elected as Viscount following his adventures in ''Inquisition''.<ref name=\"Polygon\"/>   \n\n==Conception and creation==\n[[File:Brian Bloom.jpg|thumb|180px|alt=A cropped image of Brian Bloom, Varric Tethras's voice actor|[[Brian Bloom]], the voice of Varric.]]\nVarric was originally written as a sleazy and untrustworthy character. The development team later decided to add a companion who would stand up for the protagonist of ''Dragon Age II'' given all the opposing personalities in the party, and Varric eased into the place.<ref name=\"Creating\"/> In order to find Varric's voice, Bloom would metaphorically \"gargle glass and [[Scotch whisky|scotch]] and [[sharks teeth]]\".<ref name=\"Varric and Morrigan\"/> \n\nMary Kirby wrote Varric in both games, and is the author of ''Dragon Age: Hard in Hightown''.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> She explained in an interview that ''Hard in Hightown'' was conceived as a side project during the development of ''Inquisition'', where the staff would set aside one week every few months to work on creative projects that were related to the ''Dragon Age'' franchise but might not be included as in-game content for ''Inquisition''.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> ''Hard in Hightown'' serves as flavor text in the form of in-game codex entries, which are set at a maximum word limit of 500 words.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> Kirby noted that then-Creative Director Mike Laidlaw offered her the opportunity to flesh out and publish ''Hard in Hightown'' as a novel following the conclusion of the development cycle for ''Inquisition'' downloadable content.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> \n\nKirby originally envisioned ''Hard in Hightown'' as a [[buddy cop film|parody of the buddy cop film genre]], but later wrote it as a \"hardboiled detective story\" as she felt that [[film noir]] would better fit Varric\u2019s voice.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> The title of the book references the movie series ''[[Die Hard (film series)|Die Hard]]'', whereas other elements within the book's narrative references the ''[[Lethal Weapon (franchise)|Lethal Weapon franchise]]''.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> Kirby described ''Hard in Hightown'' as a mystery crime novel with \"more swords\", and that the plot is inspired by a combination of buddy cop films from the 1980's and the works of [[Dashiell Hammet]], in particular [[The Maltese Falcon (novel)|''The Maltese Falcon'']].<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> \n\n===Visual Design===\n{{Quote box\n| width = 35em\n| align = right\n| quote = \n\"The famed companion to the Champion of Kirkwall knows a good shirt can sell a story, and the right clothes are every bit as valuable as coin. Born a surface dwarf, Varric\u2019s dress is a subtle snub to tradition, foregoing the typical beard while making light of ostentatious merchant families\".\n| source = \u2014Character Guide<ref name=\"Kits\"/>\n}}\n\nVarric's character design is noted as a departure from the usual [[swords & sorcery]] [[stock character|dwarf archetype]], being \"clean-shaven, bare-chested, playfully roguish and broadly disinterested in the usual Dwarven concerns of mining and industry\".<ref name=\"Rock, Paper, Shotgun\"/> Varric's abundant chest hair, a signature physical cue of the character, and his perceived sex appeal has become a running gag both in-universe and with ''Dragon Age'' fandom.<ref name=\"Return\"/><ref name=\"Gamezone\"/><ref name=\"Mookychick\"/> Though he is not a romance option in either installment of the series, he can be flirted with in dialogue conversations.<ref name=\"Gamezone\"/>\n\n==Appearances==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2020}}\n===In ''Dragon Age II''===\n[[File:VarricDAII.png|thumb|upright|Varric as he appears in ''Dragon Age II''.]]\nVarric first meets Hawke a year after their arrival in Kirkwall. Varric's brother, Bartrand, rejected Hawke's request to join his expedition into the Deep Roads. The future Champion is pick-pocketed by a thief whom Varric shoots and pins to a wall using Bianca. Returning Hawke's money, Varric, having heard of Hawke's reputation for skill, competence and reliability, offers them a place on the excavation as an investor. Tagging along to help Hawke gain the necessary money, Varric requests that Hawke speak to him privately in The Hanged Man in Lowtown later. At the Hanged Man, Varric tells Hawke the excavation doesn't have a suitable route to the Deep Roads and requests Hawke get one from a Grey Warden Varric has found in the city. Varric later accompanies both Bartrand and Hawke in The Deep Roads Expedition. They encountered a Primeval Thaig with a lyrium idol within. Bartrand, enamored by the idol, locks both Hawke and Varric in the room where the idol was found and makes off with idol, leaving the other two for dead. Varric is livid over this betrayal and swears to find and kill Bartrand.\n\nHawke and Varric managed to escape the Deep Roads and the treasures they found in their expedition made the two of them extremely wealthy. Bartrand vanished after the Deep Roads expedition, and Varric had to divert his attention from searching for his wayward brother to keeping the now-abandoned family business from falling apart. Varric would then occupy his missing brother's seat in the Dwarven Merchants' Guild, though he rarely attends Guild meetings and is hardly ever seen actually occupying the chair in their hall that belongs to House Tethras. He prefers to run the Tethras financial empire from his suite at the Hanged Man Tavern.\n\nEventually, Varric's spy network discovered Bartrand has returned to Kirkwall and is staying in a mansion in Hightown. Varric enlists Hawke's aid in paying Bartrand a visit, starting the quest Family Matter. Yet when they arrived at the mansion, Varric discovers that Bartrand's guards have turned crazed and hostile. After plowing through all the enemies, Hawke and Varric discover Hugin, the last surviving servant of the household. He revealed that after Bartrand left Varric and Hawke to die in the abandoned thaig, he started hearing voices, claiming the lyrium idol was 'singing' to him. Even after selling it, Bartrand could still hear the idol and was eventually driven mad by it. He tortures the servants by cutting pieces off them to help them 'hear the song'. Bartrand also feeds the guards lyrium, which makes them go insane. Hugin begs Varric and Hawke to give a quick and merciful death to anything still alive in Bartrand\u2019s study. Varric and Hawke's party proceed to fight off Bartrand and his remaining crazed guards. Once Bartrand is defeated, Varric tries to talk to him, but it becomes clear that Bartrand is crazy - he recognizes his brother and requests he help him find the idol again before talking to someone or something in his head. Varric could be persuaded to kill Bartrand, or spare him as his descent into madness is punishment enough.\n\nWhen the conflict between Kirkwall's mage and templar organisations comes to a head following the destruction of the Kirkwall Chantry by one of Hawke's companions, the rebel mage Anders, Varric will side with Hawke regardless of which faction the player chooses to support. Varric leaves Kirkwall with Hawke at the end of the game; however, he later returned. [[Cassandra Pentaghast]], a Seeker of the Chantry, travels there to interrogate him on the Chantry's behalf, believing that Hawke is the only hope of stopping the war between the mages and the Chantry. He tells her the Champion's story in full, though he exaggerates on some details. At the end of the interrogation, Varric informs Cassandra that he does not know where Hawke is, though he very much doubts that the Champion is dead. Cassandra thanks him and allows him to leave.\n\nHe later wrote and published a book called ''The Tale of the Champion'', about the rise of his close friend Hawke and their involvement in the Kirkwall Rebellion.\n\n===In ''Dragon Age Inquisition''===\nVarric is brought to the Temple of Sacred Ashes, located near a town called Haven, by Cassandra to provide the Chantry with information on Hawke. An explosion at the temple is triggered by an entity known as the Elder One and his agents, which creates a massive portal in the sky known as the Breach, allowing multitudes of demons to escape from an otherworldly realm called the Fade into the mortal world. The explosion kills thousands, with the sole survivor being the player protagonist. Varric decides to remain to assist the Chantry forces. He later joins the Inquisition along with the protagonist, who is hailed as the Herald of Andraste due to their newfound power to banish demons as well as close the Breach and any similar portals of smaller size known as Fade Rifts.\n\nAfter the Elder One's subsequent attack on Haven forces the Inquisition to move to a fortress known as Skyhold, Varric informs the Herald of Andraste, now known as the Inquisitor, that he knows someone who might be able to help. This contact is none other than Hawke. Cassandra, who is angry that he lied to her about not knowing Hawke's whereabouts, confronts Varric about his duplicity; the player may choose to intervene.\n\nThe Inquisitor may eventually encounter a dwarven woman talking to Varric at Skyhold, discussing a possible lead on Corypheus's source of red lyrium. Eventually revealed as his on-and-off love interest, Bianca Davri, she informs the Inquisitor that the location of Bartrand's Folly has been leaked, and that there are humans carting red lyrium out by the handful though the Valammar entrance. Varric discloses that her knowledge of the thaig came from him; he sent her letters after the Deep Roads Expedition.\n\nThe Inquisitor joins the duo on a mission to seal off the entrance in Valammar. At the end of the mission, the Inquisitor or Varric will come to the conclusion that it was Bianca who leaked the location of the thaig, which will result in a confrontation between the three. She reveals that she went into the ruins herself to study the red lyrium after receiving Varric's letter. If Bartrand was kept alive during the events of ''Dragon Age II'', she will mention him as one of the reasons for going into the ruins, saying she was doing him a favour. If Varric was allowed to keep the fragment of the lyrium idol, that can also be used as a justification as she says that she was trying to help him study it. According to her research, red lyrium is corrupted with the Blight. This proves lyrium to be alive, as the Blight can only taint living things. This research led to her indirectly introducing the Elder One to red lyrium, whom she met while seeking a Grey Warden Mage.\n\nTwo years after the Inquisition's defeat of the Elder One, Varric is elected as the new Viscount of Kirkwall. Varric has been funding numerous reconstruction projects in Kirkwall, and when he publicly complained that the lack of a ruling viscount was interfering with his reconstruction operations, the city state's nobility foisted the crown on Varric since they thought his complaining was \"volunteering\". The nobles feared the responsibility of running the city state, considering the fates of their past leaders, but couldn't leave the throne vacant out of concern that it could facilitate a foreign invasion. Under his rule, Kirkwall finally resumed its place as the major trade hub in the Free Marches. He also wrote a book about the Inquisition called All This Shit Is Weird, from which Cassandra reads excerpts out loud during the credits of the ''Trespasser'' DLC.\n\n===Other appearances===\n====Comics====\nVarric has appeared in a series of [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] digital comics set in the ''Dragon Age'' universe. He appears as the central character of ''Dragon Age: Until We Sleep'', and as a supporting character in ''Dragon Age: The Silent Grove'', ''Dragon Age: Those Who Speak'', and ''Dragon Age: Knight Errant''. \n\n====Hard in Hightown====\nVarric is listed as the author of ''Dragon Age: Hard in Hightown'', a novel based on his in-universe work released in July 31, 2018. For the novel, Mary Kirby uses the character as her ''[[nom de plume]]''.<ref name=\"Polygon\"/> Kirby noted that there are \"a lot of dry dwarven observations about Kirkwall society and snide comments about the Merchants\u2019 Guild\" in the story.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> A female version of Hawke is depicted on the cover, and several characters from ''Dragon Age II'', including Hawke's companions, are portrayed in the story though their names are altered; some are cameo appearances, while others are major characters in the narrative.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/> BioWare uploaded a video of Brian Bloom reading an excerpt from ''Hard in Hightown'' on their official YouTube channel to promote the novel.<ref name=\"YouTube\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nEuh8SKLQ7k|title=Hard in Hightown with Brian Bloom|date=July 31, 2018 |publisher=BioWare|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Quote box\n| width = 35em\n| align = right\n| quote = \n\"Who doesn't love a good rogue? There are loads of contenders for this role, but Varric stands out because he's more than a joke machine. He's comfortable on the street and he'll do a dodgy deal to get by, but he does have values. He has a good heart, and he'll tell you straight if he thinks you're making an evil move. The best companions are able to give the player some friction, and I think Varric is the guy for the job. He'll gently poke fun at other companions too...\"\n| source = \u2014 Tom Senior, \"The RPG dream team\"<ref name=\"RPGDream\"/>\n}}\n\nVarric has received mostly positive reactions from video game journalists, and is considered to be one of BioWare's best characters.<ref name=\"RPGDream\"/><ref name=\"Gamestm\"/><ref name=\"Companions\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2015/12/every-bioware-companion-ever-ranked/|title=Dragon Age And Mass Effect Companions, Ranked|author= Hayley Williams|date=December 15, 2015 |publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Kimberley Wallace of ''Game Informer'' said Varric \"may have a thing for blackmail and you never can be sure he's actually telling the truth, but like a true sidekick, he never lets you down. He'll always be there with a drink in hand and a crazy story to lighten the mood.\"<ref name=\"Gameinformer\"/> Alluding to Varric's in-game reputation as a best-selling author in addition to being a \"kick-ass crossbow rogue\", Ray Ivey of [[Just Adventure]] notes that Varric's character arc in ''Dragon Age: Inquisition'' \"leads into several interesting directions, including plagiarism, spies using faked versions of his works to send nefarious messages and, hilariously, a reveal that one of the other party members (the stern Cassandra) is an almost obsessive fan of his romance serials\".<ref name=\"Killer Cast\"/> Samuel Roberts from ''PC Gamer'' named Varric as his personal favorite Bioware companion, commenting \"Varric wins out for me because he's the closest your main character gets to an actual best buddy in a BioWare title (other than maybe Garrus in ''Mass Effect'').\"<ref name=\"Best and Worst\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2014/08/26/the-best-and-worst-bioware-companions |title=The best and worst BioWare companions|author=Andy Kelly |date=November 7, 2018 |publisher=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nWithin the ''Dragon Age'' series, Varric is one of the most popular characters, with various sources describing him as a fan favorite.<ref name=\"Kirby interview\"/><ref name=\"VGU\">{{cite web |url=\nhttps://vgu.tv/2020/03/09/thoughts-on-completing-dragon-age-inquisition/ |title=THOUGHTS ON COMPLETING DRAGON AGE: INQUISITION\n|author= Allan Muir|date=March 9, 2020 |publisher=VideoGameUtopiaTV|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> A reader's poll published by IGN in December 2014 for their top ultimate RPG party choices, drawing from characters of several disparate RPG video game franchises, placed Varric at #25 under the \"Reserves\" section.<ref name=\"Poll1\">{{cite web |url= https://www.ign.com/star-wars-knights-of-the-old-republic/85193/feature/the-ultimate-rpg-party-revealed|title=THE ULTIMATE RPG PARTY REVEALED|date=December 17, 2014 |work=IGN |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> The results of a match-up poll of ''Dragon Age'' characters hosted by Bioware as part of a March Madness theme in March 2015 revealed that fans voted the ''Dragon Age: Origins'' Warden protagonist, [[Alistair (Dragon Age)|Alistair]], Varric, and [[Morrigan (Dragon Age)|Morrigan]] as preferred party leader, warrior, rogue and mage in an ideal party respectively.<ref name=\"March\"/>\n\nIn response to the announcement that ''Hard in Hightown'' was being published as a real-life novel, Ethan Grach from ''Kotaku'' felt that it was \"an odd time\" for the publication of a ''Dragon Age'' book, noting the [[meta-reference|meta-referential nature]] of the novel and that Varric\u2019s \"writerly success is more of a punchline than anything else as evidenced by the title\".<ref name=\"Kotaku\">{{cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/dragon-ages-varric-is-getting-his-famous-book-published-1821844977|title=Dragon Age's Varric Is Getting His Famous Book Published For Real|author= Ethan Grach|date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Kotaku|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>  He opined that the text-based War Table mission involving Varric's in-universe work was \"one of the more memorable missions you get to direct from a BioWare menu system and yet probably not the kind lore Dragon Age fans are most curious to see expanded upon while they wait to hear about what\u2019s next for the series.\"<ref name=\"Kotaku\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Dragon Age characters|List of ''Dragon Age'' characters]]\n*[[Characters of Dragon Age: Inquisition|Characters of ''Dragon Age Inquisition'']]\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Creating\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2013/08/23/creating-dragon-age-party-members.aspx|date=August 23, 2013|title = Creating Dragon Age Party Members|author= Kimberley Wallace |website=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Mookychick\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mookychick.co.uk/reviews/video-games/trans-friendly-dragon-age-inquisition-krem-de-la-creme.php|date=February 1, 2015|title = Trans-Friendly Dragon Age: Inquisition Is Krem De La Creme|author=Matt Dean|website=Mookychick|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gamestm\">{{cite web |url= http://www.gamestm.co.uk/features/biowares-8-most-memorable-companions/|title=BioWare\u2019s 8 most memorable companions|date=June 23, 2015 |work=Gamestm |accessdate=October 26, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623074447/http://www.gamestm.co.uk/features/biowares-8-most-memorable-companions/  |archivedate=June 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gamezone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gamezone.com/originals/the-lack-of-varric-loving-leaves-us-wondering/|date=August 28, 2014|title = The lack of Varric loving leaves us wondering|author= Jenni Lada |website=Game Zone|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Killer Cast\">{{cite web |url=http://www.justadventure.com/index.php/2013-05-20-21-09-14/2617-dragon-age-inquisition-diary-6-a-killer-cast |title=Dragon Age: Inquisition Diary 6: A Killer Cast |author=Ray Ivey |date=February 4, 2015 |publisher=Just Adventure |accessdate=April 5, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6XZCuLexB?url=http://www.justadventure.com/index.php/2013-05-20-21-09-14/2617-dragon-age-inquisition-diary-6-a-killer-cast |archivedate=April 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hightown\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/dragon-ages-varric-just-got-a-real-life-publishing-deal-for-his-novel-hard-in-hightown/|date=January 7, 2018 |title = Dragon Age's Varric just got a real-life publishing deal for his novel, Hard in Hightown| author=Samuel Horti |website=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kits\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.bioware.com/2014/02/20/dragon-age-inquisition-character-kits-2/ |title= Character Kits of Cassandra and Varric|author= Conal Pierse|date=February 20, 2014 |publisher=BioWare |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"March\">{{cite web |url=https://www.inquisitr.com/1952738/dragon-age-inquisition-fans-pick-their-favorite-characters-in-march-madness-faceoff/|date=March 24, 2015|title = \u2018Dragon Age: Inquisition\u2019 Fans Pick Their Favorite Characters In March Madness Faceoff|author= David Stonecipher |website=[[Inquisitr]]|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Polygon\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/7/30/17630476/dragon-age-hard-in-hightown-book-dark-horse-varric-tethras|date=July 30, 2018 |title= Dragon Age\u2019s fake novel is a real book now, so we interviewed its author, Varric Tethras|author=Susana Polo |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gameinformer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2013/08/15/the-best-bioware-characters.aspx?PostPageIndex=1 |title=The Best BioWare Characters |author=Kimberley Wallace |date=August 15, 2013 |work=Game Informer |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> \n\n<ref name=\"Rock, Paper, Shotgun\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/01/06/dragon-age-varric-publishing-real-novel/|date=January 6, 2018|title=Fictional Dragon Age dwarf publishes actual real novel|author= \nDominic Tarason|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RPGDream\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-rpg-dream-team|date=June 9, 2017 |title=The RPG dream teams|website=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Varric and Morrigan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vg247.com/2014/03/28/dragon-ages-varric-and-morrigan-discuss-voice-acting/ |title=Dragon Age's Varric and Morrigan discuss voice acting |author=Brenna Hillier |date=March 28, 2014 |publisher=VG247 |accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Darrah interview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2014/04/22/dragon-age-inquisition-interview-on-fan-feedback-romance-returning-characters-and-the-open-world/ |title=Dragon Age: Inquisition interview - on fan feedback, romance, returning characters and the open world |author=Chris Thursten |date=April 22, 2014 |publisher=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Return\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2014/05/06/the-return-of-varric-in-dragon-age-inquisition.aspx|date=May 6, 2014|title = The Return Of Varric In Dragon Age: Inquisition|author= Kimberley Wallace |website=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kirby interview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.heypoorplayer.com/2018/01/10/interview-mary-kirby-hard-in-hightown/|date=January 10, 2018|title = INTERVIEW: BIOWARE\u2019S MARY KIRBY ABOUT UPCOMING DRAGON AGE NOVELLA \u2018HARD IN HIGHTOWN\u2019|author= Aimee Hart|website=Hey Poor Player|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ea.com/en-au/games/dragon-age/dragon-age-inquisition/characters/varric-tethras Varric Tethras] on the official ''Dragon Age: Inquisition'' website\n*[http://blog.bioware.com/2014/02/20/dragon-age-inquisition-character-kits-2/ Character Kits of Cassandra and Varric] on the official BioWare blog\n\n{{Dragon Age}}\n\n[[Category:Dragon Age characters]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video game characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional dwarves]]\n[[Category:Fictional tricksters]]\n[[Category:Dwarves in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2011]]\n[[Category:Video game sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Video game nobility]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Varric_Tethras"}
{"title_page": "Derrick Henry", "text_new": "{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = ES Puto\n| image               = Derrick Henry 2019 12-08.jpg\n| image_size          = 300px\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Henry with the Titans in 2019\n| current_team        = Tennessee Titans\n| number              = 22\n| position            = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1994|1|04|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Yulee, Florida]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 3\n| weight_lbs          = 247\n| high_school         = [[Yulee High School|Yulee (FL)]]\n| college             = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| draftyear           = 2016\n| draftround          = 2\n| draftpick           = 45\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2016}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Active\n| highlights          = \n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* [[List of National Football League rushing champions|NFL rushing yards leader]] ([[2019 NFL season|2019]])\n*[[List of National Football League annual rushing touchdowns leaders|NFL rushing touchdowns co-leader]] (2019)\n* [[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP national champion]] ([[2016 College Football Playoff National Championship|2015]])\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2015)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2015)\n* [[Doak Walker Award]] (2015)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2015)\n* Unanimous [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2015 College Football All-America Team|2015]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2015 All-SEC football team|2015]])\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] (2015)\n* [[Yulee High School|Yulee]] Hornets No. 2 retired\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[2012 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2012]])\n* [[Mr. Football Award (Florida)|Florida's Mr. Football]] (2012)\n* NFL record 99-yard rushing touchdown (Tied with [[Tony Dorsett]])\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Rushing yards]] \n|statvalue1=3,833\n|statlabel2=[[Average|Rushing average]]\n|statvalue2=4.7\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdown|Rushing touchdowns]]\n|statvalue3=38\n|statlabel4=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]] \n|statvalue4=57\n|statlabel5=[[Receiving yards]] \n|statvalue5=578\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]] \n|statvalue6=3\n| nflnew              = derrickhenry/2556075\n}}\n\n'''Derrick Lamar Henry Jr.'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00.htm |title=Derrick Henry Pro-Football-Reference Profile |website=rbref.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.titansonline.com/team/roster/derrick-henry/d85e93d3-9b5b-4d72-ab2c-3775141d6f8c/ |title=Derrick Henry Bio |website=TitansOnline.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> (born January 4, 1994) is an [[American football]] [[running back]] for the [[Tennessee Titans]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] for the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama Crimson Tide]] and was drafted in the second round of the [[2016 NFL draft]] by the Titans. In December 2015, he broke [[Herschel Walker]]'s single-season college rushing yards record in the SEC. He won the 2015 [[Heisman Trophy]], as well as the [[Doak Walker Award]], the [[Maxwell Award]], and the [[Walter Camp Award]]. Henry holds the national [[high school football]] record for career rushing yards. He [[List of National Football League rushing champions|led the NFL in rushing yards]] for the [[2019 NFL season|2019 season]], as well as [[List of National Football League annual rushing touchdowns leaders|rushing touchdowns]] (tied with [[Green Bay Packers]] running back [[Aaron Jones (running back)|Aaron Jones]]).\n\n==Early life==\nHenry attended [[Yulee High School]] in [[Yulee, Florida]], where he was a three-sport star in football, basketball, and track. He played as a running back for the Yulee Hornets [[high school football|football]] team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/8640707/derrick-henry-yulee-fla-high-school-breaks-career-high-school-rushing-record |title=Bama commit Henry breaks H.S. rushing record |last=Tyson |first=Derek |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He ran for 2,465 yards and 26 touchdowns as a freshman in 2009. He was named a first-team All-Coast at running back in 2010 after rushing for 2,788 yards and 38 touchdowns while averaging 8.9 yards per attempt. He rushed for 2,610 yards and 34 scores as a junior in 2011 to earn first-team All-Coast honors from the ''[[Florida Times-Union]]''. He set the Florida high school record with a 510-yard performance against [[Andrew Jackson High School (Jacksonville, Florida)|Jacksonville Jackson]] and averaged 9.2 yards per carry and 327.8 yards per game as a senior, finishing the season with a state-record 4,261 yards and 55 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/derrick_henry_844044.html |title=Derrick Henry Bio \u2013 ROLLTIDE.COM \u2013 University of Alabama Official Athletic Site |publisher=Rolltide.Com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He finished his high school football career with 12,124 career rushing yards, which broke [[Kenneth Hall (American football)|Ken Hall]]'s career record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/8640707/derrick-henry-yulee-fla-high-school-breaks-career-high-school-rushing-record |title=Derrick Henry of Yulee (Fla.) High School breaks career high school rushing record |date=November 17, 2012 |publisher=Espn.go.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/16/derrick-henry-high-school-rushing-record-yulee_n_2148221.html |title=Derrick Henry Breaks High School Rushing Record: Yulee Running Back Tops Ken Hall's Yards Mark |date=November 16, 2012 |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He also rushed for 153 career touchdowns. His career touchdown totals rank fifth all-time. In four years at Yulee he averaged more than 250 yards a game and never rushed for fewer than 100 yards in a game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fanbuzz.com/nfl/derrick-henry-hs-history/ |title=Derrick Henry is the Greatest High School RB Ever. It\u2019s Not Even Close. |last=Pinak |first=Patrick |date=August 14, 2019 |website=FanBuzz - Sports News - NFL {{!}} NCAA {{!}} NBA {{!}}  WWE |language=en |access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> He played for the East squad in the [[US Army All-American Bowl|2013 U.S. Army All-American Bowl]], where he rushed for 53 yards with a touchdown and a two-point conversion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jacksonville.com/sports/high-schools/2013-01-05/story/derrick-henry-scores-td-us-army-all-american-bowl |title=Derrick Henry scores TD in U.S. Army All-American Bowl |publisher=jacksonville.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.yahoo.com/news/derrick-henry-ridiculous-high-school-210857751.html |title=Derrick Henry\u2019s ridiculous high school career |website=sports.yahoo.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a [[track & field]] athlete, Henry competed as a sprinter at Yulee from 2010 to 2011. He posted a personal-best time of 11.11 seconds in the 100-meter dash at the 2011 FHSAA 2A District 3 Championships, where he placed seventh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.athletic.net/TrackAndField/Athlete.aspx?AID=2423475 |title=Derrick Henry \u2013 FL Track and Field Profile |publisher=Athletic.net |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He was also a member of the 4\u00d7100 and 4\u00d7400 squads.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/derrick-henry-2421/ |title=Derrick Henry &#124; Alabama RB |publisher=Trackingfootball.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930194729/https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/derrick-henry-2421/ |archive-date=September 30, 2015 |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nConsidered a five-star recruit by [[ESPN.com]], Henry was listed as the No. 1 athlete (player with no designated position) in the nation in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/player/_/id/108717/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry \u2013 Football Recruiting \u2013 Player Profiles \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> After originally committing to the [[University of Georgia]], Henry committed to the University of Alabama on September 28, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/8436374/record-setting-rb-derrick-henry-commits-alabama-crimson-tide |title=Record-setting RB Derrick Henry commits to Alabama Crimson Tide |date=September 29, 2012 |publisher=Espn.go.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He held offers from many of the top college football programs in the country, including USC, Notre Dame, Tennessee, Florida, and Clemson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4710 |title=Derrick Henry - Football |website=University of Alabama Athletics |language=en |access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> His number was eventually retired by Yulee.\n\n===High school statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#008000; color:#FFD700;\"  | Derrick Henry\n! colspan=\"6\" | Rushing\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP\n! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Yds/G !! Lng !! TD\n|-\n! 2009 !! Yulee\n|| 11 || 313 || 2,465 || 7.9 || 224.1 || \u2013 || 26\n|-\n! 2010 !! Yulee\n|| 12 || 313 || 2,788 || 8.9 || 232.3 || 75 || 38\n|-\n! 2011 !! Yulee\n|| 12 || 309 || 3,165 || 10.2 || 263.7 || 90 || 34\n|-\n! 2012 !! Yulee\n|| 13 || '''462''' || '''4,261''' || '''9.2''' || '''327.8''' || 80 || '''55'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Career\n! 48 !! 1,397 !! style=\"background-color:#E0CEF2; width:3em\" | 12,124 !! 8.7 !! 252.6 !! 90 !! 153\n|}\n\n==College career==\nHenry attended and played college football for the University of Alabama from 2013 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2.html |title=Derrick Henry College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He majored in Communication. He graduated on May 4, 2018.<ref name=\"Graduation\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.seccountry.com/alabama/derrick-henry-graduation-motivation |title=Derrick Henry explains why graduating from Alabama was so important to him |last=Hall |first=Jason |date=May 4, 2018 |publisher=seccountry.com |access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref> That same day, he published an article in ''[[The Players' Tribune]]'' thanking his late grandmother for the inspiration to continue pursuing his degree.<ref name=\"Graduation\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theplayerstribune.com/en-us/articles/derrick-henry-titans-alabama-grandmother |title=I Did It, Grandma |last=Henry |first=Derrick |date=May 4, 2018 |publisher=[[The Players' Tribune]] |access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2013 season===\n{{see also|2013 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n[[File: Derrick Henry All-American Bowl.jpg|thumb|left|Henry (No. 2) at the [[U.S. Army All-American Bowl]] in 2013]]\n\nAs a [[true freshman]] in 2013, Henry rushed for 382 yards on 36 carries with three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2/gamelog/2013/ |title=Derrick Henry 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On October 19, against [[2013 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]], he had 111 rushing yards and his first collegiate rushing touchdown in the 52\u20130 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2013-10-19-alabama.html |title=Arkansas at Alabama Box Score, October 19, 2013 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On November 23, against [[2013 Chattanooga Mocs football team|Chattanooga]], he had six carries for 66 yards and his second rushing touchdown of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2013-11-23-alabama.html |title=Chattanooga at Alabama Box Score, November 23, 2013 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During the [[2014 Sugar Bowl]], he rushed for 100 yards and a touchdown on eight carries and had a 61-yard touchdown reception in the 45\u201331 loss to the [[2013 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma Sooners]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-01-02-alabama.html |title=Sugar Bowl \u2013 Oklahoma vs Alabama Box Score, January 2, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/ncaaf-dr-saturday/alabama-derrick-henry-breaks-100-yards-two-touchdowns-062434988--ncaaf.html |title=Alabama\u2019s Derrick Henry breaks out for 100 yards and two touchdowns in Sugar Bowl loss |last=Bromberg |first=Nick |date=January 3, 2014 |website=Yahoo! Sports |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> In that game, Spanish-language broadcaster Pablo Viruega nicknamed him \"El Tractorcito\" (The Little Tractor) due to his long stride and powerful gait on ESPN Deportes. The nickname became a popular internet meme.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/the_story_behind_derrick_henry.html |title=The story behind Derrick Henry's 'Tractorcito' nickname and the announcer who coined it |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |date=December 22, 2014 |website=AL.com |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2014 season===\n{{see also|2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n\nIn the 2014 season, Henry shared time in the backfield with [[T. J. Yeldon]]. In the season opener against [[2014 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|West Virginia]], he had 113 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-08-30-alabama.html |title=West Virginia vs Alabama Box Score, August 30, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On September 20, against [[2014 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], he had 111 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-09-20-alabama.html |title=Florida at Alabama Box Score, September 20, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On October 18 against [[2014 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]], he had 70 rushing yards, one rushing touchdown, and a 41-yard receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-18-alabama.html |title=Texas A&M at Alabama Box Score, October 18, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the following game against [[2014 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] at [[Neyland Stadium]], he had 78 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-25-tennessee.html |title=Alabama at Tennessee Box Score, October 25, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On November 22, against [[2014 Western Carolina Catamounts football team|Western Carolina]], he had 92 rushing yards, two rushing touchdowns, and a nine-yard receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-11-22-alabama.html |title=Western Carolina at Alabama Box Score, November 22, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the [[Iron Bowl|annual rivalry game]] against [[2014 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], he had 72 rushing yards and a touchdown in the high-scoring 55\u201344 installment of the rivalry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-11-29-alabama.html |title=Auburn at Alabama Box Score, November 29, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2014 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship]] against [[2014 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]], he had 141 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns in the victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-12-06-missouri.html |title=Alabama vs Missouri Box Score, December 6, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Alabama qualified for the [[College Football Playoff]] and faced off against [[2014 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] in the National Semifinals in the [[2015 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2014-schedule.html |title=2014 Alabama Crimson Tide Schedule and Results |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Henry had 95 rushing yards, one rushing touchdown, and two receptions for 54 yards as Alabama fell 42\u201335 to the Buckeyes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-01-01-alabama.html |title=Sugar Bowl \u2013 Ohio State vs Alabama Box Score, January 1, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In his sophomore year, Henry rushed for 990 yards on 172 carries with 11 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2/gamelog/2014/ |title=Derrick Henry 2014 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 season: National Championship and Heisman season===\n{{see also|2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n\nAfter Yeldon left for the NFL, Henry took over as the starting running back as a junior in 2015. In the season opener against [[2015 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], he had 147 rushing yards and three rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-05-alabama.html |title=Wisconsin vs Alabama Box Score, September 5, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against [[2015 Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders football team|Middle Tennessee State]], he had 96 rushing yards and another game with three rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-12-alabama.html |title=Middle Tennessee State at Alabama Box Score, September 12, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game against [[2015 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], he had 127 rushing yards, one rushing touchdown, and five receptions for 39 yards in Alabama's only loss of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-19-alabama.html |title=Ole Miss at Alabama Box Score, September 19, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> After rushing for 52 yards against [[2015 Louisiana\u2013Monroe Warhawks football team|Louisiana\u2013Monroe]], he had 148 rushing yards and a touchdown in a victory over [[2015 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-26-alabama.html |title=Louisiana-Monroe at Alabama Box Score, September 26, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-03-georgia.html |title=Alabama at Georgia Box Score, October 3, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On October 10, he rushed for 95 yards and a touchdown against [[2015 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-10-alabama.html |title=Arkansas at Alabama Box Score, October 10, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> After the victory over the Razorbacks, he went on an impressive stretch of performances. On October 17, against [[2015 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]], he had 236 rushing yards, two rushing touchdowns, and an 18-yard reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-17-texas-am.html |title=Alabama at Texas A&M Box Score, October 17, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a narrow 19\u201314 victory over [[2015 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], he had 143 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-24-alabama.html |title=Tennessee at Alabama Box Score, October 24, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the following game, a much-anticipated matchup with fellow Heisman contender [[Leonard Fournette]], he had 210 rushing yards and three rushing touchdowns against [[2015 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-07-alabama.html |title=LSU at Alabama Box Score, November 7, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against [[2015 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]], he had 204 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-14-mississippi-state.html |title=Alabama at Mississippi State Box Score, November 14, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against [[2015 Charleston Southern Buccaneers football team|Charleston Southern]], he had 68 rushing yards and two more rushing touchdowns in a limited role in the 56\u20136 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-21-alabama.html |title=Charleston Southern at Alabama Box Score, November 21, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the Iron Bowl against [[2015 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], he had 271 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown on 46 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-28-auburn.html |title=Alabama at Auburn Box Score, November 28, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2015 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship]] against [[2015 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], he had 44 carries for 189 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-12-05-alabama.html |title=Florida vs Alabama Box Score, December 5, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Alabama qualified for the College Football Playoff and faced off against [[2015 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]] in the National Semifinals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2015-schedule.html |title=2015 Alabama Crimson Tide Schedule and Results |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the 38\u20130 victory over the Spartans in the [[2015 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)|Cotton Bowl]], he had 75 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-12-31-alabama.html |title=Cotton Bowl \u2013 Michigan State vs Alabama Box Score, December 31, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During Alabama's 45\u201340 victory over Clemson in the [[2016 College Football Playoff National Championship]], he rushed for 158 yards on 36 carries with three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-01-11-clemson.html |title=College Football Championship \u2013 Alabama vs Clemson Box Score, January 11, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During the game, he also broke [[Shaun Alexander]]'s record for most career rushing yards in Alabama history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14552244 |title=Henry sets school rushing mark as Tide win title |last=Miller |first=Ted |date=January 12, 2016 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Playing in all 15 games, he rushed for [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] records 2,219 yards and 28 touchdowns on 395 carries. In addition, he scored at least one touchdown in each game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2/gamelog/2015/ |title=Derrick Henry 2015 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2015/12/derrick_henry_breaks_hershel_w.html |title=Derrick Henry breaks Herschel Walker's SEC rushing record |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |date=December 5, 2015 |work=AL.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2015/12/derrick_henry_breaks_sec_recor.html |title=Alabama RB Derrick Henry breaks SEC record for single season rushing TDs |last=Zenitz |first=Matt |date=January 1, 2016 |work=AL.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Henry won the Heisman Trophy, beating out finalists [[Christian McCaffrey]] and [[Deshaun Watson]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14346202 |title=Alabama's Henry runs off with Heisman victory |last=Scarborough |first=Alex |date=December 12, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 3, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He won numerous other awards including the Doak Walker Award, Walter Camp Award, and Maxwell Award.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14340074 |title=Bama's Henry wins Maxwell, Doak Walker awards |date=December 11, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 3, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He declared for the 2016 NFL Draft after his junior season.<ref name=\"Graduation\" />\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#9e1b32; color:#ffffff;\" | Derrick Henry || colspan=\"5\" | Rushing  || colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] !! [[2013 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|| 35 || 382 || 10.6 || 80T || 3 || 1 || 61 || 61.0 || 61T || 1\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] !! [[2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|| 172 || 990 || 5.8 || 49 || 11 || 5 || 133 || 26.6 || 49 || 2\n|-\n! [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] !! [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] \n|| 395 || 2,219 || 5.6 || 74T || 28 || 11 || 91 || 8.3 || 28 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Career\n! 602 !! 3,591 !! 6.0 !! 80T !! 42 !! 17 !! 285 !! 16.8 !! 61T !! 3\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nComing out of Alabama, Henry was projected by the majority of analysts to be either drafted in the late first or second round. He was the overall consensus second best running back available behind Ohio State's [[Ezekiel Elliott]]. Scouts regarded his main assets to be his large frame, violent running, ability to break tackles with ease, speed, long strides, superior conditioning, and consistent play. The main concerns were about the wear and tear his body took as a workhorse at Alabama, his slow acceleration, average foot quickness, below-average catching ability, narrow based running style, sluggish cutbacks, and running tall.<ref name=\"profile\">[http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/derrick-henry?id=2555221 NFL Scouting Combine profile]</ref>\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 2\u215d\n|       weight = 247\n|         dash = 4.54\n|    ten split = 1.60\n| twenty split = 2.67\n|      shuttle = 4.38\n|   cone drill = 7.20\n|     vertical =37\n|     broad ft =10\n|     broad in =10\n|        bench = 22\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 33\n|    hand span = 8\u00be\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/derrick-henry?id=2555221 |title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles \u2013 Derrick Henry |website=NFL.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=127274&draftyear=2016&genpos=RB |title=*Derrick Henry \u2013 Alabama, RB : 2016 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile |website=NFL Draft Scout |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nHenry was drafted by the [[Tennessee Titans]] in the second round (45th overall) of the [[2016 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/draft.htm |title=2016 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He was the second running back taken that year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/tiny.fcgi?id=IVmR8 |title=Draft Finder Query Results |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He was reunited with his former fullback at Alabama [[Jalston Fowler]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/oti/2016.htm |title=2016 Tennessee Titans Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2016 season: Rookie year===\n{{see also|2016 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn May 9, 2016, the Tennessee Titans signed Henry to a four-year, $5.40 million contract with $3.30 million guaranteed and a signing bonus of $2.13 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amp.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000660841/article/tennessee-titans-sign-derrick-henry-to-rookie-contract |title=Tennessee Titans sign Derrick Henry to rookie contract |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=May 9, 2016 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHenry began his rookie season as the backup running back to veteran [[DeMarco Murray]]. He wore the No. 2 jersey throughout training camp and preseason and donned the No. 22 once running back [[Dexter McCluster]] was cut on September 2, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/187/TEN |title=Ourlads.com: Tennessee Titan's depth chart |website=ourlads.com |access-date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHenry made his NFL debut and earned his first NFL start in the Titans' season-opening loss to the [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]]. He finished the game with five carries for three yards and two receptions for 41 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609110oti.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Tennessee Titans \u2013 September 11th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During Week 8, Henry scored his first NFL touchdown on a 6-yard rush in a 36\u201322 victory over the [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]]. He finished the game with 16 carries for a then career-high 60 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown and four catches for 37 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610270oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 October 27th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On December 18, 2016, he had nine rushing attempts for 58 rushing yards and a season-high two rushing touchdowns in a 19\u201317 road victory over the [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612180kan.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 December 18th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During the season finale against the [[2016 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he ran for a then-career-high 65 rushing yards on 15 carries and scored a touchdown in the 24\u201317 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701010oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans \u2013 January 1st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished his rookie season with 110 carries for 490 yards (both 6th among NFL rookies in 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/jHjUb |title=Rookie rushing, 2015 season, NFL |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref>) and five touchdowns in 15 games and two starts. He also caught 13 passes for 137 yards.<ref name=\"glog\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00/gamelog/ |title=Derrick Henry 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NFL\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/derrickhenry/2556075/profile |title=NFL Player Profile: Derrick Henry |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season===\n{{see also|2017 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nHenry split carries with DeMarco Murray and run-oriented quarterback [[Marcus Mariota]]. During Week 2, Henry ran for 92 yards and a touchdown on 14 carries in a 37\u201316 road victory against the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/ea1b7c3f35084556b0166affd9235e27 |title=Henry comes home, carries load for Titans late in 37-16 win |last=Long |first=Mark |date=September 17, 2017 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> On October 16, 2017, on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', Henry ran for a career-best 131 yards on 19 carries, including a 72-yard touchdown late in the fourth quarter of the 36\u201322 victory over the [[2017 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]]. In addition, he had a reception for 14 receiving yards in the victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710160oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans \u2013 October 16th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During Week 13, Henry ran for 109 yards on 11 carries and beat his longest rush of the year with a 75-yard rushing touchdown late in the fourth quarter of the 24\u201313 victory over the [[2017 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712030oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 3rd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the regular season finale against the Jaguars, Henry caught his first receiving touchdown on a 66-yard reception from [[Marcus Mariota]] in the 15\u201310 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712310oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 31st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Titans finished second in the [[AFC South]] with a 9\u20137 record and made the playoffs as a Wild Card team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/standings/_/season/2017 |title=2017 NFL Regular Season Standings \u2013 National Football League |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.titansonline.com/news/article-4/Titans-Beat-Jaguars-Punch-Ticket-to-Playoffs/5a96d12b-a9bc-4231-8bfa-baba96b4e1b6 |title=Titans Beat Jaguars, Punch Ticket to Playoffs |last=Wyatt |first=Jim |date=December 31, 2017 |access-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107175020/http://www.titansonline.com/news/article-4/Titans-Beat-Jaguars-Punch-Ticket-to-Playoffs/5a96d12b-a9bc-4231-8bfa-baba96b4e1b6 |archive-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: Tennessee Titans 22, Kansas City Chiefs 21|Wild Card Round]], the Titans played the [[2017 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]]. Because DeMarco Murray was out with a knee injury, Henry got the start.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/01/04/demarco-murray-out-titans-chiefs-playoffs-wild-card |title=DeMarco Murray will not play against Chiefs Saturday |date=January 4, 2018 |work=SI.com |access-date=January 7, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In a 22-21 road victory, Henry had the best performance of his career up to that point, rushing for 156 yards and a touchdown on 23 carries and catching two passes for 35 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801060kan.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 January 6th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/3043078/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> His 191 yards-from-scrimmage was a franchise record. In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Tennessee Titans 14|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Henry had 28 rushing yards and 21 receiving yards in the 35\u201314 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots \u2013 January 13th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished the regular season with 176 carries for 744 rushing yards and five touchdowns in 15 games and two starts. He also caught 11 passes for 136 receiving yards and a touchdown. In the postseason, Henry ran for 184 yards and a touchdown on 35 carries and caught five passes for 56 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Derrick Henry 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season===\n{{see also|2018 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File: Derrick Henry 2018 08-09.jpg|thumb|left|Henry in 2018]]\n\nHenry split carries with offseason acquisition [[Dion Lewis]] and run-oriented quarterback Marcus Mariota for most of the 2018 season. During Week 2, Henry recorded an eight-yard pass completion, the first of his career, to wide receiver [[Taywan Taylor]] in the Titans' 20\u201317 victory over the [[2018 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2018/09/16/derrick-henry-wildcat-titans-texans-marcus-mariota/1328116002/ |title=With Marcus Mariota sidelined, Derrick Henry operates Titans' offense out of Wildcat |last=Bacharach |first=Erik |date=September 16, 2018 |work=The Tennessean |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> He also had 18 carries in that game and the next against the [[2018 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], but was used much less frequently through the middle of the season.\n\nFrom Weeks 4-13, Henry averaged nine carries for only 37 yards per game, and never rushed for over 60 yards.<ref name=glog /> This all changed in Week 14 against the Jaguars. In the second quarter, Henry had a 99-yard touchdown run, fending off three tacklers, tying him with [[Tony Dorsett]] for the longest NFL touchdown run. He finished the game with four rushing touchdowns and 238 rushing yards on 17 carries, breaking [[Chris Johnson (running back)|Chris Johnson]]'s franchise record of 228 yards in [[2009 Tennessee Titans season|2009]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812060oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 6th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3043078/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2018/12/06/tennessees-derrick-henry-ties-franchise-record-fourth-td-chris-johnson-titans/2204607002/ |title=Titans' Derrick Henry sets franchise rushing record on four-touchdown night |last=Deas |first=Tommy |date=December 6, 2018 |website=The Tennessean |access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref> He also became the ninth player in NFL history to record a 200+ yard and 4+ touchdown game, and the first to do so on fewer than 22 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/etmZH |title=All 200-yard, 4-TD rushing games in NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref> His 238 rushing yards were the most by any player for a single game for the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/y4vgK |title=Most rushing yards, single game, 2018 season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Henry was named the AFC Offensive Player of the Week due to his spectacular performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000998979/article/derrick-henry-amari-cooper-among-nfl-players-of-the-week |title=Derrick Henry, Amari Cooper among NFL Players of the Week |last=Knoblauch |first=Austin |date=December 12, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> During Week 15, the Titans went on the road to face the [[2018 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]. In a cold and rainy game, Henry led the NFL in rushing for the second consecutive week with 170 yards and two touchdowns on a career-high 33 carries, along with a one-yard reception and six-yard pass completion in the 17\u20130 shutout.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812160nyg.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at New York Giants \u2013 December 16th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> In Weeks 16 and 17, he combined for 177 rushing yards and a touchdown in the two games against the [[2018 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] and [[2018 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812220oti.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 22nd, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812300oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 30th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> He was later named the AFC Offensive Player of the Month for December.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001007288/article/titans-derrick-henry-among-nfl-players-of-the-month |title=Titans' Derrick Henry among NFL Players of the Month |last=Baca |first=Michael |date=January 3, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished the 2018 season with 1,059 rushing yards, 12 rushing touchdowns, and 15 receptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/nfl/tennessee-titans/Article/Derrick-Henry-eclipses-1000-yards-rushing-for-first-time-127088460/ |title=Derrick Henry eclipses 1,000 yards rushing for first time |last=Cotton |first=Dan |date=December 31, 2018 |website=Tennessee Titans |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> After the season, he was ranked 99th on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/sports/2019/07/derrick-henry-makes-debut-in-top-100-players.html |title=Derrick Henry makes debut in \u2018Top 100 Players\u2019 |last=Inabinett |first=Mark |date=July 22, 2019 |website=AL.com |access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season: Rushing yards leader===\n{{see also|2019 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File: Derrick Henry 2019 10-13.jpg|thumb|Henry in 2019]]\n[[File:Derrick Henry.png|thumb|Henry after throwing a touchdown pass in the AFC Divisional Playoffs against the [[Baltimore Ravens]] ]]\nIn the season opener against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Henry rushed 19 times for 84 yards and a touchdown. He also caught one pass for a 75-yard touchdown as the Titans won on the road 43\u201313.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127928 |title=Mariota, Titans sack Mayfield, hyped Browns 43-13 in opener |date=September 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 2 against the [[2019 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he rushed 15 times for 81 yards and a touchdown as the Titans narrowly lost 19\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128114 |title=Brissett spoils Titans' opener, rallying Colts to 19-17 win |date=September 15, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 15, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Two weeks later against the [[2019 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Henry had his first 100-yard game of the season when he rushed for 100 yards on 27 carries in a 24\u201310 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/mariota-throws-3-first-half-td-passes-titans-drop-falcons/ |title=Mariota throws 3 first-half TD passes, Titans drop Falcons |date=September 29, 2019 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], he rushed for 78 yards and a touchdown as the Titans lost by a score of 14\u20137.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/titans-lose-defensive-slugfest-to-bills-14-7?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Titans Lose in Frustrating Fashion to Bills, 14-7 |last=Wyatt |first=Jim |date=October 6, 2019 |website=Titans Online |language=en-US |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> After a season-low 28 yards in a Week 6 shutout loss to [[2019 Denver Broncos season|Denver]], Henry sank to 12th in the league in rushing, over 200 yards behind the league leaders he would eventually catch.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/5SVtz |title=Rushing leaderboard, Week 6, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Henry responded with 90 rushing yards and a touchdown in a 23\u201320 victory against the [[2019 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]] in Week 7.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127979 |title=Casey recovers fumble, Titans hold off Chargers' rally 23-20 |date=October 20, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 20, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 9 against the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], Henry rushed 13 times for 63 yards and a touchdown and caught three passes for 36 yards and a touchdown in the 30\u201320 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128078 |title=McCaffrey scores 3 TDs as Panthers defeat Titans 30-20 |date=November 3, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 3, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he finished with 188 rushing yards and two touchdowns as the Titans narrowly won 35\u201332.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127981 |title=Titans rally, spoil Mahomes' return beating Chiefs 35-32 |date=November 10, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 10, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Henry won the [[FedEx Air & Ground NFL Players of the Week|FedEx Ground Player of the Week]] for his efforts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://titansized.com/2019/11/15/titans-derrick-henry-wins-fedex-ground/amp/ |title=Tennessee Titans: Derrick Henry wins FedEx Ground Player of the Week |last=Moraitis, Michael |date=November 15, 2019 |website=TitansSized.com |access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> During a Jaguars rematch in Week 12 after a Week 11 bye, Henry had a 74-yard rushing touchdown in the third quarter. Overall, he finished the 42\u201320 victory with 159 rushing yards and two touchdowns along with one reception for 16 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128000 |title=Titans explode for 4 TDs in 6 plays, rout Jaguars 42-20 |date=November 24, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 24, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the next game, a rematch against the Colts, he rushed 26 times for 149 yards and a touchdown in the 31\u201317 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128058 |title=Blocked field goal helps Titans turn table with win at Indy |date=December 1, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 1, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 14 against the [[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], Henry rushed for 103 yards and two touchdowns in the 42\u201321 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128005 |title=Titans win 4th straight, 42-21 over Raiders |date=December 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During the season finale against the [[2019 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] in Week 17, Henry finished with 211 rushing yards and three touchdowns as the Titans won 35\u201314 and made it to the playoffs as a Wild card team. During the game, Henry narrowly won the [[List of National Football League rushing champions|2019 rushing title]] over [[Nick Chubb]] of the Cleveland Browns, with the winning rush being a 53-yard touchdown run.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titans RB Derrick Henry Captures NFL Rushing Title in Playoff-Clinching Win|url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/titans-rb-derrick-henry-captures-nfl-rushing-title-in-playoff-clinching-win|author=Wyatt, Jim|website=TitansOnline.com|date=December 29, 2019|access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref> This was Henry's first career rushing crown and the first Titan to win it since [[Chris Johnson (running back)|Chris Johnson]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127984 |title=Titans clinch playoff spot with 35-14 win over Texans |date=December 29, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished the regular season setting career-highs in carries with 303, rushing yards with 1,540, and rushing touchdowns with 16, which all led the league, despite only playing in 15 games, missing the Week 16 game against the New Orleans Saints due to a hamstring injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28350845/titans-star-rb-derrick-henry-hamstring-inactive-saints |title=Titans star RB Derrick Henry (hamstring) inactive against Saints |date=December 22, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> He also set career-highs in receptions with 16, receiving yards with 206, and receiving touchdowns with two.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Derrick Henry 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>  On December 17, 2019, he was selected to his first [[Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2019/12/17/derrick-henry-brett-kern-titans-pro-bowl/2681124001/ |title=Titans' Derrick Henry, Brett Kern named to 2020 Pro Bowl |last=Bacharach |first=Erik |date=December 17, 2019 |website=www.Tennessean.com |access-date=January 3, 2020 |agency=The Tennessean}}</ref> On January 3, 2020, he was named to the second-team [[All-Pro]] at both the running back and flex position, both behind [[Christian McCaffrey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2020/01/03/nfl-ap-all-pro-team-2019-list-voting-titans-brett-kern-derrick-henry/2804859001/ |title=Brett Kern, Derrick Henry named to 2019 NFL AP All-Pro team |date=January 3, 2020|agency=The Tennessean |website=www.Tennessean.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith the Titans finishing the season 9\u20137, the team narrowly clinched a wild card spot for the #6 seed. In the AFC Wild Card game against the defending Super Bowl champ [[2019 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], which was played on his 26th birthday, Henry rushed for over 100 yards and a touchdown in the first half, finishing with 182 yards (the most ever against a [[Bill Belichick]]-led team, and the third most ever in a postseason road game) and a 22-yard reception in the 20\u201313 victory. Henry became the first rushing champion with a 100-yard playoff game since [[Terrell Davis]] in 1998, the first to win a playoff game since [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] in 2007, and the second Titan with multiple post-season 100+ rushing games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tennessee Titans vs. New England Patriots [01/04/2020] |url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2020010401/2019/WC1/titans@patriots |website=www.nfl.com}}</ref> He also broke his own franchise record for most yards-from-scrimmage with 204.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131036 |title=Derrick Henry, Titans stun Patriots 20-13 in wild-card upset |date=January 4, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> During the AFC Divisional Round against the [[2019 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Henry rushed 30 times for 195 yards and threw a 3-yard touchdown pass to wide receiver [[Corey Davis (wide receiver)|Corey Davis]] in the 28\u201312 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131041 |title=Titans stun Ravens, head to AFC title game with 28-12 win |date=January 11, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> He became the second player in history with three postseason games with 150+ rushing yards (Terrell Davis had 4), and the only player with 175+ in consecutive games (Davis is the only other with two in a career).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/AP3WJ |title=150+ rushing yard games, postseason, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\nIn the AFC Championship game against the Kansas City Chiefs, Henry was mostly held in check.  During the game, he rushed 19 times for 69 yards and a touchdown in the 35\u201324 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131044 |title=Mahomes' feet, arms, lift Chiefs to Super Bowl over Titans |date=January 19, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2020 season===\n{{see also|2020 Tennessee Titans season}}\nOn March 16, 2020, the Titans placed the franchise tag on Henry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106340/article/titans-place-franchise-tag-on-rb-derrick-henry |title=Titans place franchise tag on RB Derrick Henry |last=Shook |first=Nick |date=March 16, 2020 |website=NFL.com |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> He signed the tag on April 2, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Shook |first=Nick |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108179/article/titans-rb-derrick-henry-signs-franchise-tender |title=Titans RB Derrick Henry signs franchise tender |date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n| Led the league\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffd700; width:3em;\" |\n| NFL Record\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! colspan=\"2\" | Games\n! colspan=\"5\" | Rushing\n! colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"2\" | Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! [[2016 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| 15 || 2 || 110 || 490 || 4.5 || 22 || 5 || 13 || 137 || 10.5 || 29 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| '''16''' || 2 || 176 || 744 || 4.2 || 75T || 5 || 11 || 136 || '''12.4''' || 66T || 1 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| '''16''' || 12 || 215 || 1,059 || 4.9 || style=\"background:#ffd700; width:3em;\"|'''99T''' || 12 || 15 || 99 || 6.6 || 21 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| 15 || '''15''' || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| '''303''' || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|'''1,540''' || '''5.1''' || 74T || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| '''16''' || '''18''' || '''206''' || 11.4 || '''75T''' || '''2''' || '''5''' || '''3'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 62 !! 31 !! 804 !! 3,833 !! 4.8 !! 99T !! 38 !! 57 !! 578 !! 10.1 !! 75T !! 3 !! 7 !! 4\n|}\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/3043078/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry Stats |website=ESPN |language=en |access-date=September 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Postseason====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! colspan=\"2\" | Games\n! colspan=\"5\" | Rushing\n! colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"2\" | Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs|2017]] !! [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| 2 || 2 || 35 || 184 || 5.3 || 35T || 1 || '''5''' || '''56''' || '''11.2''' || '''29''' || 0 || '''1''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2019\u201320 NFL playoffs|2019]] !! [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]]\n| '''3''' || '''3''' || '''83''' || '''446''' || '''5.4''' || '''66''' || '''2''' || '''5''' || 21 || 4.2 || 22 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 5 !! 5 !! 118 !! 630 !! 5.3 !! 66 !! 3 !! 10 !! 77 !! 7.7 !! 29 !! 0 !! 1 !! 0\n|}\n<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===NFL records===\n* First player to record a 200+-yard and 4+-touchdown game on fewer than 22 carries<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/titans-vs-jaguars-final-score-takeaways-derrick-henrys-record-night-99-yard-td-run-lead-tennessee-win/ |title=Titans vs. Jaguars final score, takeaways: Derrick Henry's record night, 99-yard TD run lead Tennessee win |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n* Tied for longest run in NFL history at 99 yards ([[Tony Dorsett]] - 1982)<ref name=\"Knoblauch\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000996734/article/derrick-henry-ties-nfl-record-with-historic-99yard-td |title=Derrick Henry ties NFL record with historic 99-yard TD |last=Knoblauch |first=Austin |date=December 6, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* First player in NFL history with 180+ rushing yards in three consecutive games<ref name=\"al.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/sports/2020/01/derrick-henry-the-only-player-in-nfl-history.html |title=Derrick Henry: \u2018The only player in NFL history \u2026\u2019 |date=January 12, 2020 |website=AL.com |access-date=January 13, 2020 |agency=Al.com}}</ref>\n* Most rushing yards in first 4 playoff games: 561<ref name=\"al.com\"/>\n* First player to have 180+ rushing yards in consecutive playoff games<ref name=\"al.com\"/>\n* Most rushing yards in any eight-game stretch in NFL history: 1,273\n\n====Titans franchise records====\n* Most rushing yards in a game: 238 (2018-12-06 JAX)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/nfl/tennessee-titans/Article/Derrick-Henry-franchise-rushing-record-126011175/ |title=Derrick Henry breaks Titans rushing record |last=Newby |first=John |date=December 6, 2018 |website=Tennessee Titans |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n* Most rushing yards in back-to-back games: 408<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/sports/professional/story/2018/dec/19/derrick-henry-focused-helping-titans-win-not/485263/ |title=Derrick Henry focused on helping Titans win, not reaching 1,000 rushing yards |date=December 19, 2018 |website=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]] |access-date=January 30, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n* Most rushing yards in a postseason game: 195 (2020-01-11 @BAL)<ref name=\"al.com\"/>\n* Most rushing touchdowns in a game: 4 (2018-12-06 JAX, tied with [[Earl Campbell]] 1978)\n* Most scrimmage yards in a postseason game: 204 (2020-01-11 @BAL)<ref>{{cite web |title=Titans with 150+ Yards-from-Scrimmage, postseason |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/XzC62 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref>\n* Most 100+ rushing yard postseason games: 3\n* Most 2+ TD games in a season: 6 (2019; tied with [[Bill Groman]] and [[Chris Johnson (running back)|Chris Johnson]])\n* Longest rushing play: 99 yards<ref name=\"Knoblauch\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Henry and Miller.png|thumb|Henry alongside [[Von Miller]] at the [[2020 Pro Bowl]] ]]\nHenry's late grandmother, Gladys Henry, helped raise him and played a key inspirational role in his development. In 2018, he fulfilled a promise to her and graduated from Alabama in May 2018 with a bachelor's degree in communications.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ftw/2018/05/05/derrick-henry-writes-emotional-letter-to-late-grandmother-after-graduating-from-alabama/111160330/ |title=Derrick Henry writes letter to late grandma for graduation |last=Martinelli |first=Michelle R.|date=May 5, 2018 |website=USA TODAY |language=en-US |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> He has a portrait tattoo of her on his chest. She nicknamed him \"Shocka\" as a baby because he \"shocked the whole family\" when he was born. He also has a dog named Nino.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.titansonline.com/team/players-roster/derrick-henry/?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Derrick Henry Biography |website=Titans Online |language=en-US |access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* [https://twitter.com/KingHenry_2?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Twitter]\n* [https://www.titansonline.com/team/players-roster/derrick-henry/ Tennessee Titans bio]\n* [https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4710 Alabama Crimson Tide bio]\n* {{Heisman|id=345|name=Derrick Henry}}\n\n{{Tennessee Titans roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Heisman Trophy}}\n{{Maxwell Award}}\n{{Walter Camp Award}}\n{{Doak Walker Award}}\n{{2015 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{Tennessee Titans 2016 draft navbox}}\n{{FedEx NFL Players}}\n{{NFL rushing yards leaders}}\n{{NFL rushing touchdowns leaders}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henry, Derrick}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yulee, Florida]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Heisman Trophy winners]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Derrick Henry\n| image               = Derrick Henry 2019 12-08.jpg\n| image_size          = 300px\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Henry with the Titans in 2019\n| current_team        = Tennessee Titans\n| number              = 22\n| position            = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1994|1|04|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Yulee, Florida]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 3\n| weight_lbs          = 247\n| high_school         = [[Yulee High School|Yulee (FL)]]\n| college             = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| draftyear           = 2016\n| draftround          = 2\n| draftpick           = 45\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2016}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Active\n| highlights          = \n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* [[List of National Football League rushing champions|NFL rushing yards leader]] ([[2019 NFL season|2019]])\n*[[List of National Football League annual rushing touchdowns leaders|NFL rushing touchdowns co-leader]] (2019)\n* [[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP national champion]] ([[2016 College Football Playoff National Championship|2015]])\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2015)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2015)\n* [[Doak Walker Award]] (2015)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2015)\n* Unanimous [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2015 College Football All-America Team|2015]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2015 All-SEC football team|2015]])\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] (2015)\n* [[Yulee High School|Yulee]] Hornets No. 2 retired\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[2012 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2012]])\n* [[Mr. Football Award (Florida)|Florida's Mr. Football]] (2012)\n* NFL record 99-yard rushing touchdown (Tied with [[Tony Dorsett]])\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Rushing yards]] \n|statvalue1=3,833\n|statlabel2=[[Average|Rushing average]]\n|statvalue2=4.7\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdown|Rushing touchdowns]]\n|statvalue3=38\n|statlabel4=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]] \n|statvalue4=57\n|statlabel5=[[Receiving yards]] \n|statvalue5=578\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]] \n|statvalue6=3\n| nflnew              = derrickhenry/2556075\n}}\n\n'''Derrick Lamar Henry Jr.'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00.htm |title=Derrick Henry Pro-Football-Reference Profile |website=rbref.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.titansonline.com/team/roster/derrick-henry/d85e93d3-9b5b-4d72-ab2c-3775141d6f8c/ |title=Derrick Henry Bio |website=TitansOnline.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> (born January 4, 1994) is an [[American football]] [[running back]] for the [[Tennessee Titans]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] for the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama Crimson Tide]] and was drafted in the second round of the [[2016 NFL draft]] by the Titans. In December 2015, he broke [[Herschel Walker]]'s single-season college rushing yards record in the SEC. He won the 2015 [[Heisman Trophy]], as well as the [[Doak Walker Award]], the [[Maxwell Award]], and the [[Walter Camp Award]]. Henry holds the national [[high school football]] record for career rushing yards. He [[List of National Football League rushing champions|led the NFL in rushing yards]] for the [[2019 NFL season|2019 season]], as well as [[List of National Football League annual rushing touchdowns leaders|rushing touchdowns]] (tied with [[Green Bay Packers]] running back [[Aaron Jones (running back)|Aaron Jones]]).\n\n==Early life==\nHenry attended [[Yulee High School]] in [[Yulee, Florida]], where he was a three-sport star in football, basketball, and track. He played as a running back for the Yulee Hornets [[high school football|football]] team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/8640707/derrick-henry-yulee-fla-high-school-breaks-career-high-school-rushing-record |title=Bama commit Henry breaks H.S. rushing record |last=Tyson |first=Derek |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He ran for 2,465 yards and 26 touchdowns as a freshman in 2009. He was named a first-team All-Coast at running back in 2010 after rushing for 2,788 yards and 38 touchdowns while averaging 8.9 yards per attempt. He rushed for 2,610 yards and 34 scores as a junior in 2011 to earn first-team All-Coast honors from the ''[[Florida Times-Union]]''. He set the Florida high school record with a 510-yard performance against [[Andrew Jackson High School (Jacksonville, Florida)|Jacksonville Jackson]] and averaged 9.2 yards per carry and 327.8 yards per game as a senior, finishing the season with a state-record 4,261 yards and 55 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/derrick_henry_844044.html |title=Derrick Henry Bio \u2013 ROLLTIDE.COM \u2013 University of Alabama Official Athletic Site |publisher=Rolltide.Com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He finished his high school football career with 12,124 career rushing yards, which broke [[Kenneth Hall (American football)|Ken Hall]]'s career record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/8640707/derrick-henry-yulee-fla-high-school-breaks-career-high-school-rushing-record |title=Derrick Henry of Yulee (Fla.) High School breaks career high school rushing record |date=November 17, 2012 |publisher=Espn.go.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/16/derrick-henry-high-school-rushing-record-yulee_n_2148221.html |title=Derrick Henry Breaks High School Rushing Record: Yulee Running Back Tops Ken Hall's Yards Mark |date=November 16, 2012 |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He also rushed for 153 career touchdowns. His career touchdown totals rank fifth all-time. In four years at Yulee he averaged more than 250 yards a game and never rushed for fewer than 100 yards in a game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fanbuzz.com/nfl/derrick-henry-hs-history/ |title=Derrick Henry is the Greatest High School RB Ever. It\u2019s Not Even Close. |last=Pinak |first=Patrick |date=August 14, 2019 |website=FanBuzz - Sports News - NFL {{!}} NCAA {{!}} NBA {{!}}  WWE |language=en |access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> He played for the East squad in the [[US Army All-American Bowl|2013 U.S. Army All-American Bowl]], where he rushed for 53 yards with a touchdown and a two-point conversion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jacksonville.com/sports/high-schools/2013-01-05/story/derrick-henry-scores-td-us-army-all-american-bowl |title=Derrick Henry scores TD in U.S. Army All-American Bowl |publisher=jacksonville.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.yahoo.com/news/derrick-henry-ridiculous-high-school-210857751.html |title=Derrick Henry\u2019s ridiculous high school career |website=sports.yahoo.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a [[track & field]] athlete, Henry competed as a sprinter at Yulee from 2010 to 2011. He posted a personal-best time of 11.11 seconds in the 100-meter dash at the 2011 FHSAA 2A District 3 Championships, where he placed seventh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.athletic.net/TrackAndField/Athlete.aspx?AID=2423475 |title=Derrick Henry \u2013 FL Track and Field Profile |publisher=Athletic.net |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He was also a member of the 4\u00d7100 and 4\u00d7400 squads.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/derrick-henry-2421/ |title=Derrick Henry &#124; Alabama RB |publisher=Trackingfootball.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930194729/https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/derrick-henry-2421/ |archive-date=September 30, 2015 |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nConsidered a five-star recruit by [[ESPN.com]], Henry was listed as the No. 1 athlete (player with no designated position) in the nation in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/player/_/id/108717/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry \u2013 Football Recruiting \u2013 Player Profiles \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> After originally committing to the [[University of Georgia]], Henry committed to the University of Alabama on September 28, 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/8436374/record-setting-rb-derrick-henry-commits-alabama-crimson-tide |title=Record-setting RB Derrick Henry commits to Alabama Crimson Tide |date=September 29, 2012 |publisher=Espn.go.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> He held offers from many of the top college football programs in the country, including USC, Notre Dame, Tennessee, Florida, and Clemson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=4710 |title=Derrick Henry - Football |website=University of Alabama Athletics |language=en |access-date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> His number was eventually retired by Yulee.\n\n===High school statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#008000; color:#FFD700;\"  | Derrick Henry\n! colspan=\"6\" | Rushing\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP\n! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Yds/G !! Lng !! TD\n|-\n! 2009 !! Yulee\n|| 11 || 313 || 2,465 || 7.9 || 224.1 || \u2013 || 26\n|-\n! 2010 !! Yulee\n|| 12 || 313 || 2,788 || 8.9 || 232.3 || 75 || 38\n|-\n! 2011 !! Yulee\n|| 12 || 309 || 3,165 || 10.2 || 263.7 || 90 || 34\n|-\n! 2012 !! Yulee\n|| 13 || '''462''' || '''4,261''' || '''9.2''' || '''327.8''' || 80 || '''55'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Career\n! 48 !! 1,397 !! style=\"background-color:#E0CEF2; width:3em\" | 12,124 !! 8.7 !! 252.6 !! 90 !! 153\n|}\n\n==College career==\nHenry attended and played college football for the University of Alabama from 2013 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2.html |title=Derrick Henry College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He majored in Communication. He graduated on May 4, 2018.<ref name=\"Graduation\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.seccountry.com/alabama/derrick-henry-graduation-motivation |title=Derrick Henry explains why graduating from Alabama was so important to him |last=Hall |first=Jason |date=May 4, 2018 |publisher=seccountry.com |access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref> That same day, he published an article in ''[[The Players' Tribune]]'' thanking his late grandmother for the inspiration to continue pursuing his degree.<ref name=\"Graduation\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theplayerstribune.com/en-us/articles/derrick-henry-titans-alabama-grandmother |title=I Did It, Grandma |last=Henry |first=Derrick |date=May 4, 2018 |publisher=[[The Players' Tribune]] |access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2013 season===\n{{see also|2013 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n[[File: Derrick Henry All-American Bowl.jpg|thumb|left|Henry (No. 2) at the [[U.S. Army All-American Bowl]] in 2013]]\n\nAs a [[true freshman]] in 2013, Henry rushed for 382 yards on 36 carries with three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2/gamelog/2013/ |title=Derrick Henry 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On October 19, against [[2013 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]], he had 111 rushing yards and his first collegiate rushing touchdown in the 52\u20130 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2013-10-19-alabama.html |title=Arkansas at Alabama Box Score, October 19, 2013 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On November 23, against [[2013 Chattanooga Mocs football team|Chattanooga]], he had six carries for 66 yards and his second rushing touchdown of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2013-11-23-alabama.html |title=Chattanooga at Alabama Box Score, November 23, 2013 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During the [[2014 Sugar Bowl]], he rushed for 100 yards and a touchdown on eight carries and had a 61-yard touchdown reception in the 45\u201331 loss to the [[2013 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma Sooners]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-01-02-alabama.html |title=Sugar Bowl \u2013 Oklahoma vs Alabama Box Score, January 2, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/ncaaf-dr-saturday/alabama-derrick-henry-breaks-100-yards-two-touchdowns-062434988--ncaaf.html |title=Alabama\u2019s Derrick Henry breaks out for 100 yards and two touchdowns in Sugar Bowl loss |last=Bromberg |first=Nick |date=January 3, 2014 |website=Yahoo! Sports |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> In that game, Spanish-language broadcaster Pablo Viruega nicknamed him \"El Tractorcito\" (The Little Tractor) due to his long stride and powerful gait on ESPN Deportes. The nickname became a popular internet meme.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/the_story_behind_derrick_henry.html |title=The story behind Derrick Henry's 'Tractorcito' nickname and the announcer who coined it |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |date=December 22, 2014 |website=AL.com |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2014 season===\n{{see also|2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n\nIn the 2014 season, Henry shared time in the backfield with [[T. J. Yeldon]]. In the season opener against [[2014 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|West Virginia]], he had 113 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-08-30-alabama.html |title=West Virginia vs Alabama Box Score, August 30, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On September 20, against [[2014 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], he had 111 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-09-20-alabama.html |title=Florida at Alabama Box Score, September 20, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On October 18 against [[2014 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]], he had 70 rushing yards, one rushing touchdown, and a 41-yard receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-18-alabama.html |title=Texas A&M at Alabama Box Score, October 18, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the following game against [[2014 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] at [[Neyland Stadium]], he had 78 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-10-25-tennessee.html |title=Alabama at Tennessee Box Score, October 25, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On November 22, against [[2014 Western Carolina Catamounts football team|Western Carolina]], he had 92 rushing yards, two rushing touchdowns, and a nine-yard receiving touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-11-22-alabama.html |title=Western Carolina at Alabama Box Score, November 22, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the [[Iron Bowl|annual rivalry game]] against [[2014 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], he had 72 rushing yards and a touchdown in the high-scoring 55\u201344 installment of the rivalry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-11-29-alabama.html |title=Auburn at Alabama Box Score, November 29, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2014 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship]] against [[2014 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]], he had 141 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns in the victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-12-06-missouri.html |title=Alabama vs Missouri Box Score, December 6, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Alabama qualified for the [[College Football Playoff]] and faced off against [[2014 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] in the National Semifinals in the [[2015 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2014-schedule.html |title=2014 Alabama Crimson Tide Schedule and Results |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Henry had 95 rushing yards, one rushing touchdown, and two receptions for 54 yards as Alabama fell 42\u201335 to the Buckeyes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-01-01-alabama.html |title=Sugar Bowl \u2013 Ohio State vs Alabama Box Score, January 1, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In his sophomore year, Henry rushed for 990 yards on 172 carries with 11 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2/gamelog/2014/ |title=Derrick Henry 2014 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015 season: National Championship and Heisman season===\n{{see also|2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n\nAfter Yeldon left for the NFL, Henry took over as the starting running back as a junior in 2015. In the season opener against [[2015 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], he had 147 rushing yards and three rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-05-alabama.html |title=Wisconsin vs Alabama Box Score, September 5, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against [[2015 Middle Tennessee Blue Raiders football team|Middle Tennessee State]], he had 96 rushing yards and another game with three rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-12-alabama.html |title=Middle Tennessee State at Alabama Box Score, September 12, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game against [[2015 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], he had 127 rushing yards, one rushing touchdown, and five receptions for 39 yards in Alabama's only loss of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-19-alabama.html |title=Ole Miss at Alabama Box Score, September 19, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> After rushing for 52 yards against [[2015 Louisiana\u2013Monroe Warhawks football team|Louisiana\u2013Monroe]], he had 148 rushing yards and a touchdown in a victory over [[2015 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-09-26-alabama.html |title=Louisiana-Monroe at Alabama Box Score, September 26, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-03-georgia.html |title=Alabama at Georgia Box Score, October 3, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On October 10, he rushed for 95 yards and a touchdown against [[2015 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-10-alabama.html |title=Arkansas at Alabama Box Score, October 10, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> After the victory over the Razorbacks, he went on an impressive stretch of performances. On October 17, against [[2015 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]], he had 236 rushing yards, two rushing touchdowns, and an 18-yard reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-17-texas-am.html |title=Alabama at Texas A&M Box Score, October 17, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, a narrow 19\u201314 victory over [[2015 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], he had 143 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-10-24-alabama.html |title=Tennessee at Alabama Box Score, October 24, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the following game, a much-anticipated matchup with fellow Heisman contender [[Leonard Fournette]], he had 210 rushing yards and three rushing touchdowns against [[2015 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-07-alabama.html |title=LSU at Alabama Box Score, November 7, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against [[2015 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]], he had 204 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-14-mississippi-state.html |title=Alabama at Mississippi State Box Score, November 14, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, against [[2015 Charleston Southern Buccaneers football team|Charleston Southern]], he had 68 rushing yards and two more rushing touchdowns in a limited role in the 56\u20136 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-21-alabama.html |title=Charleston Southern at Alabama Box Score, November 21, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the Iron Bowl against [[2015 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], he had 271 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown on 46 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-11-28-auburn.html |title=Alabama at Auburn Box Score, November 28, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2015 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship]] against [[2015 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], he had 44 carries for 189 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-12-05-alabama.html |title=Florida vs Alabama Box Score, December 5, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> Alabama qualified for the College Football Playoff and faced off against [[2015 Michigan State Spartans football team|Michigan State]] in the National Semifinals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2015-schedule.html |title=2015 Alabama Crimson Tide Schedule and Results |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the 38\u20130 victory over the Spartans in the [[2015 Cotton Bowl Classic (December)|Cotton Bowl]], he had 75 rushing yards and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2015-12-31-alabama.html |title=Cotton Bowl \u2013 Michigan State vs Alabama Box Score, December 31, 2015 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During Alabama's 45\u201340 victory over Clemson in the [[2016 College Football Playoff National Championship]], he rushed for 158 yards on 36 carries with three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2016-01-11-clemson.html |title=College Football Championship \u2013 Alabama vs Clemson Box Score, January 11, 2016 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During the game, he also broke [[Shaun Alexander]]'s record for most career rushing yards in Alabama history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14552244 |title=Henry sets school rushing mark as Tide win title |last=Miller |first=Ted |date=January 12, 2016 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Playing in all 15 games, he rushed for [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] records 2,219 yards and 28 touchdowns on 395 carries. In addition, he scored at least one touchdown in each game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/derrick-henry-2/gamelog/2015/ |title=Derrick Henry 2015 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2015/12/derrick_henry_breaks_hershel_w.html |title=Derrick Henry breaks Herschel Walker's SEC rushing record |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |date=December 5, 2015 |work=AL.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2015/12/derrick_henry_breaks_sec_recor.html |title=Alabama RB Derrick Henry breaks SEC record for single season rushing TDs |last=Zenitz |first=Matt |date=January 1, 2016 |work=AL.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Henry won the Heisman Trophy, beating out finalists [[Christian McCaffrey]] and [[Deshaun Watson]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14346202 |title=Alabama's Henry runs off with Heisman victory |last=Scarborough |first=Alex |date=December 12, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 3, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He won numerous other awards including the Doak Walker Award, Walter Camp Award, and Maxwell Award.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14340074 |title=Bama's Henry wins Maxwell, Doak Walker awards |date=December 11, 2015 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 3, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He declared for the 2016 NFL Draft after his junior season.<ref name=\"Graduation\" />\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#9e1b32; color:#ffffff;\" | Derrick Henry || colspan=\"5\" | Rushing  || colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] !! [[2013 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|| 35 || 382 || 10.6 || 80T || 3 || 1 || 61 || 61.0 || 61T || 1\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] !! [[2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|| 172 || 990 || 5.8 || 49 || 11 || 5 || 133 || 26.6 || 49 || 2\n|-\n! [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] !! [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] \n|| 395 || 2,219 || 5.6 || 74T || 28 || 11 || 91 || 8.3 || 28 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Career\n! 602 !! 3,591 !! 6.0 !! 80T !! 42 !! 17 !! 285 !! 16.8 !! 61T !! 3\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nComing out of Alabama, Henry was projected by the majority of analysts to be either drafted in the late first or second round. He was the overall consensus second best running back available behind Ohio State's [[Ezekiel Elliott]]. Scouts regarded his main assets to be his large frame, violent running, ability to break tackles with ease, speed, long strides, superior conditioning, and consistent play. The main concerns were about the wear and tear his body took as a workhorse at Alabama, his slow acceleration, average foot quickness, below-average catching ability, narrow based running style, sluggish cutbacks, and running tall.<ref name=\"profile\">[http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/derrick-henry?id=2555221 NFL Scouting Combine profile]</ref>\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 2\u215d\n|       weight = 247\n|         dash = 4.54\n|    ten split = 1.60\n| twenty split = 2.67\n|      shuttle = 4.38\n|   cone drill = 7.20\n|     vertical =37\n|     broad ft =10\n|     broad in =10\n|        bench = 22\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 33\n|    hand span = 8\u00be\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/derrick-henry?id=2555221 |title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles \u2013 Derrick Henry |website=NFL.com |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=127274&draftyear=2016&genpos=RB |title=*Derrick Henry \u2013 Alabama, RB : 2016 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile |website=NFL Draft Scout |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nHenry was drafted by the [[Tennessee Titans]] in the second round (45th overall) of the [[2016 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/draft.htm |title=2016 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He was the second running back taken that year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/tiny.fcgi?id=IVmR8 |title=Draft Finder Query Results |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> He was reunited with his former fullback at Alabama [[Jalston Fowler]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/oti/2016.htm |title=2016 Tennessee Titans Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2016 season: Rookie year===\n{{see also|2016 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nOn May 9, 2016, the Tennessee Titans signed Henry to a four-year, $5.40 million contract with $3.30 million guaranteed and a signing bonus of $2.13 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amp.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000660841/article/tennessee-titans-sign-derrick-henry-to-rookie-contract |title=Tennessee Titans sign Derrick Henry to rookie contract |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=May 9, 2016 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHenry began his rookie season as the backup running back to veteran [[DeMarco Murray]]. He wore the No. 2 jersey throughout training camp and preseason and donned the No. 22 once running back [[Dexter McCluster]] was cut on September 2, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/187/TEN |title=Ourlads.com: Tennessee Titan's depth chart |website=ourlads.com |access-date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHenry made his NFL debut and earned his first NFL start in the Titans' season-opening loss to the [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]]. He finished the game with five carries for three yards and two receptions for 41 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609110oti.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Tennessee Titans \u2013 September 11th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During Week 8, Henry scored his first NFL touchdown on a 6-yard rush in a 36\u201322 victory over the [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]]. He finished the game with 16 carries for a then career-high 60 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown and four catches for 37 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610270oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 October 27th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On December 18, 2016, he had nine rushing attempts for 58 rushing yards and a season-high two rushing touchdowns in a 19\u201317 road victory over the [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612180kan.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 December 18th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During the season finale against the [[2016 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he ran for a then-career-high 65 rushing yards on 15 carries and scored a touchdown in the 24\u201317 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701010oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans \u2013 January 1st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished his rookie season with 110 carries for 490 yards (both 6th among NFL rookies in 2016<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/jHjUb |title=Rookie rushing, 2015 season, NFL |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref>) and five touchdowns in 15 games and two starts. He also caught 13 passes for 137 yards.<ref name=\"glog\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00/gamelog/ |title=Derrick Henry 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NFL\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/derrickhenry/2556075/profile |title=NFL Player Profile: Derrick Henry |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season===\n{{see also|2017 Tennessee Titans season}}\n\nHenry split carries with DeMarco Murray and run-oriented quarterback [[Marcus Mariota]]. During Week 2, Henry ran for 92 yards and a touchdown on 14 carries in a 37\u201316 road victory against the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/ea1b7c3f35084556b0166affd9235e27 |title=Henry comes home, carries load for Titans late in 37-16 win |last=Long |first=Mark |date=September 17, 2017 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> On October 16, 2017, on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', Henry ran for a career-best 131 yards on 19 carries, including a 72-yard touchdown late in the fourth quarter of the 36\u201322 victory over the [[2017 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]]. In addition, he had a reception for 14 receiving yards in the victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710160oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans \u2013 October 16th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> During Week 13, Henry ran for 109 yards on 11 carries and beat his longest rush of the year with a 75-yard rushing touchdown late in the fourth quarter of the 24\u201313 victory over the [[2017 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712030oti.htm |title=Houston Texans at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 3rd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref> In the regular season finale against the Jaguars, Henry caught his first receiving touchdown on a 66-yard reception from [[Marcus Mariota]] in the 15\u201310 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712310oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 31st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Titans finished second in the [[AFC South]] with a 9\u20137 record and made the playoffs as a Wild Card team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/standings/_/season/2017 |title=2017 NFL Regular Season Standings \u2013 National Football League |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.titansonline.com/news/article-4/Titans-Beat-Jaguars-Punch-Ticket-to-Playoffs/5a96d12b-a9bc-4231-8bfa-baba96b4e1b6 |title=Titans Beat Jaguars, Punch Ticket to Playoffs |last=Wyatt |first=Jim |date=December 31, 2017 |access-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107175020/http://www.titansonline.com/news/article-4/Titans-Beat-Jaguars-Punch-Ticket-to-Playoffs/5a96d12b-a9bc-4231-8bfa-baba96b4e1b6 |archive-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: Tennessee Titans 22, Kansas City Chiefs 21|Wild Card Round]], the Titans played the [[2017 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]]. Because DeMarco Murray was out with a knee injury, Henry got the start.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/01/04/demarco-murray-out-titans-chiefs-playoffs-wild-card |title=DeMarco Murray will not play against Chiefs Saturday |date=January 4, 2018 |work=SI.com |access-date=January 7, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In a 22-21 road victory, Henry had the best performance of his career up to that point, rushing for 156 yards and a touchdown on 23 carries and catching two passes for 35 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801060kan.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 January 6th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/3043078/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> His 191 yards-from-scrimmage was a franchise record. In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Tennessee Titans 14|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Henry had 28 rushing yards and 21 receiving yards in the 35\u201314 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots \u2013 January 13th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished the regular season with 176 carries for 744 rushing yards and five touchdowns in 15 games and two starts. He also caught 11 passes for 136 receiving yards and a touchdown. In the postseason, Henry ran for 184 yards and a touchdown on 35 carries and caught five passes for 56 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Derrick Henry 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season===\n{{see also|2018 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File: Derrick Henry 2018 08-09.jpg|thumb|left|Henry in 2018]]\n\nHenry split carries with offseason acquisition [[Dion Lewis]] and run-oriented quarterback Marcus Mariota for most of the 2018 season. During Week 2, Henry recorded an eight-yard pass completion, the first of his career, to wide receiver [[Taywan Taylor]] in the Titans' 20\u201317 victory over the [[2018 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2018/09/16/derrick-henry-wildcat-titans-texans-marcus-mariota/1328116002/ |title=With Marcus Mariota sidelined, Derrick Henry operates Titans' offense out of Wildcat |last=Bacharach |first=Erik |date=September 16, 2018 |work=The Tennessean |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> He also had 18 carries in that game and the next against the [[2018 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], but was used much less frequently through the middle of the season.\n\nFrom Weeks 4-13, Henry averaged nine carries for only 37 yards per game, and never rushed for over 60 yards.<ref name=glog /> This all changed in Week 14 against the Jaguars. In the second quarter, Henry had a 99-yard touchdown run, fending off three tacklers, tying him with [[Tony Dorsett]] for the longest NFL touchdown run. He finished the game with four rushing touchdowns and 238 rushing yards on 17 carries, breaking [[Chris Johnson (running back)|Chris Johnson]]'s franchise record of 228 yards in [[2009 Tennessee Titans season|2009]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812060oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 6th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3043078/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2018/12/06/tennessees-derrick-henry-ties-franchise-record-fourth-td-chris-johnson-titans/2204607002/ |title=Titans' Derrick Henry sets franchise rushing record on four-touchdown night |last=Deas |first=Tommy |date=December 6, 2018 |website=The Tennessean |access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref> He also became the ninth player in NFL history to record a 200+ yard and 4+ touchdown game, and the first to do so on fewer than 22 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/etmZH |title=All 200-yard, 4-TD rushing games in NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref> His 238 rushing yards were the most by any player for a single game for the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/y4vgK |title=Most rushing yards, single game, 2018 season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> Henry was named the AFC Offensive Player of the Week due to his spectacular performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000998979/article/derrick-henry-amari-cooper-among-nfl-players-of-the-week |title=Derrick Henry, Amari Cooper among NFL Players of the Week |last=Knoblauch |first=Austin |date=December 12, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> During Week 15, the Titans went on the road to face the [[2018 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]. In a cold and rainy game, Henry led the NFL in rushing for the second consecutive week with 170 yards and two touchdowns on a career-high 33 carries, along with a one-yard reception and six-yard pass completion in the 17\u20130 shutout.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812160nyg.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at New York Giants \u2013 December 16th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=October 2, 2019}}</ref> In Weeks 16 and 17, he combined for 177 rushing yards and a touchdown in the two games against the [[2018 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] and [[2018 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812220oti.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 22nd, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812300oti.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 30th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> He was later named the AFC Offensive Player of the Month for December.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001007288/article/titans-derrick-henry-among-nfl-players-of-the-month |title=Titans' Derrick Henry among NFL Players of the Month |last=Baca |first=Michael |date=January 3, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished the 2018 season with 1,059 rushing yards, 12 rushing touchdowns, and 15 receptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/nfl/tennessee-titans/Article/Derrick-Henry-eclipses-1000-yards-rushing-for-first-time-127088460/ |title=Derrick Henry eclipses 1,000 yards rushing for first time |last=Cotton |first=Dan |date=December 31, 2018 |website=Tennessee Titans |access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> After the season, he was ranked 99th on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.al.com/sports/2019/07/derrick-henry-makes-debut-in-top-100-players.html |title=Derrick Henry makes debut in \u2018Top 100 Players\u2019 |last=Inabinett |first=Mark |date=July 22, 2019 |website=AL.com |access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season: Rushing yards leader===\n{{see also|2019 Tennessee Titans season}}\n[[File: Derrick Henry 2019 10-13.jpg|thumb|Henry in 2019]]\n[[File:Derrick Henry.png|thumb|Henry after throwing a touchdown pass in the AFC Divisional Playoffs against the [[Baltimore Ravens]] ]]\nIn the season opener against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Henry rushed 19 times for 84 yards and a touchdown. He also caught one pass for a 75-yard touchdown as the Titans won on the road 43\u201313.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127928 |title=Mariota, Titans sack Mayfield, hyped Browns 43-13 in opener |date=September 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 2 against the [[2019 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he rushed 15 times for 81 yards and a touchdown as the Titans narrowly lost 19\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128114 |title=Brissett spoils Titans' opener, rallying Colts to 19-17 win |date=September 15, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 15, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Two weeks later against the [[2019 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Henry had his first 100-yard game of the season when he rushed for 100 yards on 27 carries in a 24\u201310 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/mariota-throws-3-first-half-td-passes-titans-drop-falcons/ |title=Mariota throws 3 first-half TD passes, Titans drop Falcons |date=September 29, 2019 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=October 2, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], he rushed for 78 yards and a touchdown as the Titans lost by a score of 14\u20137.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/titans-lose-defensive-slugfest-to-bills-14-7?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Titans Lose in Frustrating Fashion to Bills, 14-7 |last=Wyatt |first=Jim |date=October 6, 2019 |website=Titans Online |language=en-US |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref> After a season-low 28 yards in a Week 6 shutout loss to [[2019 Denver Broncos season|Denver]], Henry sank to 12th in the league in rushing, over 200 yards behind the league leaders he would eventually catch.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/5SVtz |title=Rushing leaderboard, Week 6, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Henry responded with 90 rushing yards and a touchdown in a 23\u201320 victory against the [[2019 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]] in Week 7.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127979 |title=Casey recovers fumble, Titans hold off Chargers' rally 23-20 |date=October 20, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 20, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 9 against the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], Henry rushed 13 times for 63 yards and a touchdown and caught three passes for 36 yards and a touchdown in the 30\u201320 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128078 |title=McCaffrey scores 3 TDs as Panthers defeat Titans 30-20 |date=November 3, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 3, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he finished with 188 rushing yards and two touchdowns as the Titans narrowly won 35\u201332.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127981 |title=Titans rally, spoil Mahomes' return beating Chiefs 35-32 |date=November 10, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 10, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Henry won the [[FedEx Air & Ground NFL Players of the Week|FedEx Ground Player of the Week]] for his efforts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://titansized.com/2019/11/15/titans-derrick-henry-wins-fedex-ground/amp/ |title=Tennessee Titans: Derrick Henry wins FedEx Ground Player of the Week |last=Moraitis, Michael |date=November 15, 2019 |website=TitansSized.com |access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> During a Jaguars rematch in Week 12 after a Week 11 bye, Henry had a 74-yard rushing touchdown in the third quarter. Overall, he finished the 42\u201320 victory with 159 rushing yards and two touchdowns along with one reception for 16 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128000 |title=Titans explode for 4 TDs in 6 plays, rout Jaguars 42-20 |date=November 24, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 24, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the next game, a rematch against the Colts, he rushed 26 times for 149 yards and a touchdown in the 31\u201317 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128058 |title=Blocked field goal helps Titans turn table with win at Indy |date=December 1, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 1, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 14 against the [[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], Henry rushed for 103 yards and two touchdowns in the 42\u201321 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128005 |title=Titans win 4th straight, 42-21 over Raiders |date=December 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During the season finale against the [[2019 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] in Week 17, Henry finished with 211 rushing yards and three touchdowns as the Titans won 35\u201314 and made it to the playoffs as a Wild card team. During the game, Henry narrowly won the [[List of National Football League rushing champions|2019 rushing title]] over [[Nick Chubb]] of the Cleveland Browns, with the winning rush being a 53-yard touchdown run.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titans RB Derrick Henry Captures NFL Rushing Title in Playoff-Clinching Win|url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/titans-rb-derrick-henry-captures-nfl-rushing-title-in-playoff-clinching-win|author=Wyatt, Jim|website=TitansOnline.com|date=December 29, 2019|access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref> This was Henry's first career rushing crown and the first Titan to win it since [[Chris Johnson (running back)|Chris Johnson]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127984 |title=Titans clinch playoff spot with 35-14 win over Texans |date=December 29, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHenry finished the regular season setting career-highs in carries with 303, rushing yards with 1,540, and rushing touchdowns with 16, which all led the league, despite only playing in 15 games, missing the Week 16 game against the New Orleans Saints due to a hamstring injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28350845/titans-star-rb-derrick-henry-hamstring-inactive-saints |title=Titans star RB Derrick Henry (hamstring) inactive against Saints |date=December 22, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> He also set career-highs in receptions with 16, receiving yards with 206, and receiving touchdowns with two.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HenrDe00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Derrick Henry 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>  On December 17, 2019, he was selected to his first [[Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2019/12/17/derrick-henry-brett-kern-titans-pro-bowl/2681124001/ |title=Titans' Derrick Henry, Brett Kern named to 2020 Pro Bowl |last=Bacharach |first=Erik |date=December 17, 2019 |website=www.Tennessean.com |access-date=January 3, 2020 |agency=The Tennessean}}</ref> On January 3, 2020, he was named to the second-team [[All-Pro]] at both the running back and flex position, both behind [[Christian McCaffrey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nfl/titans/2020/01/03/nfl-ap-all-pro-team-2019-list-voting-titans-brett-kern-derrick-henry/2804859001/ |title=Brett Kern, Derrick Henry named to 2019 NFL AP All-Pro team |date=January 3, 2020|agency=The Tennessean |website=www.Tennessean.com |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith the Titans finishing the season 9\u20137, the team narrowly clinched a wild card spot for the #6 seed. In the AFC Wild Card game against the defending Super Bowl champ [[2019 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], which was played on his 26th birthday, Henry rushed for over 100 yards and a touchdown in the first half, finishing with 182 yards (the most ever against a [[Bill Belichick]]-led team, and the third most ever in a postseason road game) and a 22-yard reception in the 20\u201313 victory. Henry became the first rushing champion with a 100-yard playoff game since [[Terrell Davis]] in 1998, the first to win a playoff game since [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] in 2007, and the second Titan with multiple post-season 100+ rushing games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tennessee Titans vs. New England Patriots [01/04/2020] |url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2020010401/2019/WC1/titans@patriots |website=www.nfl.com}}</ref> He also broke his own franchise record for most yards-from-scrimmage with 204.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131036 |title=Derrick Henry, Titans stun Patriots 20-13 in wild-card upset |date=January 4, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> During the AFC Divisional Round against the [[2019 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Henry rushed 30 times for 195 yards and threw a 3-yard touchdown pass to wide receiver [[Corey Davis (wide receiver)|Corey Davis]] in the 28\u201312 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131041 |title=Titans stun Ravens, head to AFC title game with 28-12 win |date=January 11, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> He became the second player in history with three postseason games with 150+ rushing yards (Terrell Davis had 4), and the only player with 175+ in consecutive games (Davis is the only other with two in a career).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/AP3WJ |title=150+ rushing yard games, postseason, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\nIn the AFC Championship game against the Kansas City Chiefs, Henry was mostly held in check.  During the game, he rushed 19 times for 69 yards and a touchdown in the 35\u201324 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131044 |title=Mahomes' feet, arms, lift Chiefs to Super Bowl over Titans |date=January 19, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2020 season===\n{{see also|2020 Tennessee Titans season}}\nOn March 16, 2020, the Titans placed the franchise tag on Henry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106340/article/titans-place-franchise-tag-on-rb-derrick-henry |title=Titans place franchise tag on RB Derrick Henry |last=Shook |first=Nick |date=March 16, 2020 |website=NFL.com |access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> He signed the tag on April 2, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Shook |first=Nick |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108179/article/titans-rb-derrick-henry-signs-franchise-tender |title=Titans RB Derrick Henry signs franchise tender |date=April 2, 2020 |access-date=April 3, 2020 |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n| Led the league\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffd700; width:3em;\" |\n| NFL Record\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! colspan=\"2\" | Games\n! colspan=\"5\" | Rushing\n! colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"2\" | Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! [[2016 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| 15 || 2 || 110 || 490 || 4.5 || 22 || 5 || 13 || 137 || 10.5 || 29 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| '''16''' || 2 || 176 || 744 || 4.2 || 75T || 5 || 11 || 136 || '''12.4''' || 66T || 1 || 1 || 0\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| '''16''' || 12 || 215 || 1,059 || 4.9 || style=\"background:#ffd700; width:3em;\"|'''99T''' || 12 || 15 || 99 || 6.6 || 21 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|TEN]] \n| 15 || '''15''' || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| '''303''' || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|'''1,540''' || '''5.1''' || 74T || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| '''16''' || '''18''' || '''206''' || 11.4 || '''75T''' || '''2''' || '''5''' || '''3'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 62 !! 31 !! 804 !! 3,833 !! 4.8 !! 99T !! 38 !! 57 !! 578 !! 10.1 !! 75T !! 3 !! 7 !! 4\n|}\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/3043078/derrick-henry |title=Derrick Henry Stats |website=ESPN |language=en |access-date=September 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Postseason====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" s